00:00:42.910 --> 00:00:44.650
So I'm a social neuroscientist.

00:00:44.650 --> 00:00:48.450
I have been looking at
people's brains, mostly using

00:00:48.450 --> 00:00:52.620
MRI scanners, for about 20 years
now, a little longer than 20

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:54.070
years.

00:00:54.070 --> 00:00:57.120
And at some point
around 10, 12 years ago,

00:00:57.120 --> 00:00:59.670
I started getting
invited to come

00:00:59.670 --> 00:01:02.544
speak to different
business-related groups.

00:01:02.544 --> 00:01:03.960
And actually, a
bunch of the talks

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:08.460
were at Oracle early on and
other leadership organizations.

00:01:08.460 --> 00:01:11.820
And so it got me thinking
about, what on earth

00:01:11.820 --> 00:01:15.090
does my work have to say
that's relevant to business,

00:01:15.090 --> 00:01:18.030
to thinking about how
the social brain is

00:01:18.030 --> 00:01:19.830
doing its thing at work.

00:01:19.830 --> 00:01:24.240
And so part of what I
think about is how do we

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:27.450
promote well-being,
productivity, happiness--

00:01:27.450 --> 00:01:31.350
all these things that you
want to see more of at work?

00:01:31.350 --> 00:01:34.290
And to do this, you
basically need a good model,

00:01:34.290 --> 00:01:39.640
a good theory of what motivates
and drives human beings.

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:42.434
And so I think that the
inherited wisdom we've had

00:01:42.434 --> 00:01:44.100
for hundreds of years--
you can't really

00:01:44.100 --> 00:01:46.860
do much better than Thomas
Hobbes, who summed it up

00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:47.820
in a single sentence.

00:01:50.470 --> 00:01:52.660
"Man has no other end,
in all his actions,

00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:56.110
than his private self-interest."

00:01:56.110 --> 00:01:59.380
So we get as much good stuff
as we can for as little

00:01:59.380 --> 00:02:02.630
work, as little
pain as possible.

00:02:02.630 --> 00:02:06.550
And if you want to see
evidence of this, one easy way

00:02:06.550 --> 00:02:10.870
to see this is to go to a game
that economists developed,

00:02:10.870 --> 00:02:14.710
I think, back in the late '80s--
maybe it was the early '90s.

00:02:14.710 --> 00:02:15.640
No, it was earlier.

00:02:15.640 --> 00:02:17.840
It was the '80s. --called
the prisoner's dilemma.

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:20.770
And I'm sure some of you are
familiar with the prisoner's

00:02:20.770 --> 00:02:21.460
dilemma.

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:23.890
I won't describe all
the details of it.

00:02:23.890 --> 00:02:25.780
The key things you
need to know is

00:02:25.780 --> 00:02:28.240
that typically two
people are playing

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:30.500
with or against each other.

00:02:30.500 --> 00:02:32.470
They never meet each
other, and they are never

00:02:32.470 --> 00:02:33.710
going to meet each other.

00:02:33.710 --> 00:02:36.800
They typically play
one round of the game,

00:02:36.800 --> 00:02:39.340
so there's no concern
with reputation.

00:02:39.340 --> 00:02:42.040
And the key thing about
the way you play the game

00:02:42.040 --> 00:02:44.770
is that your outcomes
are interdependent.

00:02:44.770 --> 00:02:48.310
So the way you play affects
both your outcomes and the other

00:02:48.310 --> 00:02:49.090
person's.

00:02:49.090 --> 00:02:51.610
And the same is true
for them as well.

00:02:51.610 --> 00:02:53.890
And so there's two ways
you can play the game.

00:02:53.890 --> 00:02:56.470
You can play the
game selfishly, where

00:02:56.470 --> 00:02:58.150
you try to maximize
the amount of money

00:02:58.150 --> 00:02:59.780
you'll take for yourself.

00:02:59.780 --> 00:03:01.930
And it is definitively
going to come

00:03:01.930 --> 00:03:05.380
at the expense of less
money for the other person.

00:03:05.380 --> 00:03:10.270
And the other option is to play
in a more communal sort of way,

00:03:10.270 --> 00:03:12.310
where you try to maximize
the amount of money

00:03:12.310 --> 00:03:15.250
that you and the other person
are going to earn jointly.

00:03:15.250 --> 00:03:18.280
But that will definitely
come at the expense of you

00:03:18.280 --> 00:03:20.170
getting less money personally.

00:03:20.170 --> 00:03:22.120
These are the two options.

00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:24.370
And in line with
economists' predictions,

00:03:24.370 --> 00:03:27.670
the vast majority of people
play this game selfishly.

00:03:27.670 --> 00:03:31.000
They go and say, I'll take
the most money for myself,

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:32.320
thank you very much.

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:37.090
And so games like this give
rise to the view of human nature

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:40.900
as being something
like Homo economicus,

00:03:40.900 --> 00:03:42.820
something like that,
where we're basically

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:45.100
rationally
self-interested creatures,

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:47.230
where we're
fundamentally selfish,

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:49.240
we try not to exert
too much effort,

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:52.750
we can be reasonably
rational in some contexts,

00:03:52.750 --> 00:03:56.960
and we pursue wealth and other
material gains for ourselves.

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:58.930
And that's what's
been shown in hundreds

00:03:58.930 --> 00:04:02.470
and hundreds of iterations
of this game, the prisoner's

00:04:02.470 --> 00:04:03.280
dilemma.

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:05.380
But there's a
version of this game

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:08.560
that you are probably not
familiar with that I think

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:10.510
is an interesting contrast.

00:04:10.510 --> 00:04:12.562
So actually, it's
the exact same game.

00:04:12.562 --> 00:04:14.020
So in this version
of the game, you

00:04:14.020 --> 00:04:15.640
have the exact same
rules described

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:18.010
to you word for word the same.

00:04:18.010 --> 00:04:20.769
And you play the game
exactly the same way.

00:04:20.769 --> 00:04:23.530
But at the start of the game
when they're introducing

00:04:23.530 --> 00:04:28.270
the rules, instead of
describing or defining

00:04:28.270 --> 00:04:31.330
the game one way or another,
in this particular version

00:04:31.330 --> 00:04:33.220
of the game, they
say, today you're

00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:35.740
going to be playing
the community game.

00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:38.440
And then they explain
the exact same rules

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:42.020
as what is normally taking
place in the prisoner's dilemma.

00:04:42.020 --> 00:04:43.960
And when you do
this, the percentage

00:04:43.960 --> 00:04:47.260
of people who play selfishly
drops precipitously.

00:04:47.260 --> 00:04:49.840
And suddenly now,
almost everybody-- well,

00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:51.580
3/4 of people--

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:53.830
suddenly now play
communally and try

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:56.600
to do what's best for the group.

00:04:56.600 --> 00:05:00.910
And so in addition to
suggesting that human beings are

00:05:00.910 --> 00:05:04.090
exquisitely sensitive to context
and situational pressures

00:05:04.090 --> 00:05:07.750
and so on, what it
also may suggest

00:05:07.750 --> 00:05:11.020
is that we are more than
just Homo economicus.

00:05:11.020 --> 00:05:13.310
We are also Homo socialis--

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:18.010
that we may have these
intrinsic social concerns

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:20.260
and that what we're
looking for is

00:05:20.260 --> 00:05:23.020
when we're supposed to
demonstrate these motives

00:05:23.020 --> 00:05:25.990
and when we're supposed to
demonstrate those motives

00:05:25.990 --> 00:05:28.370
and that we have both of
these and we use both.

00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:31.000
I'm not trying to suggest
we're not selfish creatures.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:31.600
We are.

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:34.060
But we are not only
selfish creatures

00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:35.740
is part of what I'll argue.

00:05:35.740 --> 00:05:37.360
So for the time I
have with you, I'm

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:39.620
going to try to do three things.

00:05:39.620 --> 00:05:43.224
The first thing I'm going to
try to do is present to you

00:05:43.224 --> 00:05:44.890
some of the neuroscience
data that we've

00:05:44.890 --> 00:05:48.310
collected in an
attempt to prove to you

00:05:48.310 --> 00:05:51.340
that our ability and our
skills at being social

00:05:51.340 --> 00:05:53.830
is not just another
program we learn like how

00:05:53.830 --> 00:05:55.900
to play chess or algebra.

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:57.490
Those are things
that we can learn

00:05:57.490 --> 00:05:59.615
because we have this great
prefrontal cortex that's

00:05:59.615 --> 00:06:03.760
super flexible and can learn
any new rule-based kind of thing

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:06.910
if it's useful for
us to learn it.

00:06:06.910 --> 00:06:08.710
But instead, what
I'm going to suggest

00:06:08.710 --> 00:06:11.320
is that our social
operating system

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:13.930
is part of the basic
components of who

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:16.990
we are as mammals, that all
mammals actually share this

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:20.470
and we have plenty
of it as well.

00:06:20.470 --> 00:06:22.450
If I convince you of
that-- hopefully I will--

00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:24.370
I'll spend some
time, then, trying

00:06:24.370 --> 00:06:28.120
to tell you some
things about why

00:06:28.120 --> 00:06:31.180
paying more attention
to our social nature

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:34.600
is really important for thinking
about happiness, well-being,

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:37.190
and productivity
in the workplace.

00:06:37.190 --> 00:06:40.210
And then I assume
I will have time

00:06:40.210 --> 00:06:42.340
because I set a timer
for myself to make

00:06:42.340 --> 00:06:44.120
sure I get to this last piece.

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:46.720
Because that's the piece I'm
actually most excited about.

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:48.845
That's about where
our work is going

00:06:48.845 --> 00:06:52.050
and where it's now really
directly relevant to thinking

00:06:52.050 --> 00:06:55.020
about neuroscience-- and social
neuroscience, specifically--

00:06:55.020 --> 00:06:58.710
in the workplace and how we
can use it there in a way

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:01.480
that it, I think, really
hasn't been used in the past.

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:03.510
But let's start at
the beginning, trying

00:07:03.510 --> 00:07:07.440
to convince you that some of
the social aspects of ourself

00:07:07.440 --> 00:07:11.140
are really, really a
basic part of who we are.

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:15.300
So let's start with the
concept social pain.

00:07:15.300 --> 00:07:18.060
So we came up with the
concept of social pain back

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:19.380
in the early 2000s.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:22.510
And because we came up with
it, we got to define it.

00:07:22.510 --> 00:07:24.900
And so our definition--
there's various ones

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:27.240
we've used-- but it's
the pain associated

00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:31.030
with actual or potential threats
to one's social connections.

00:07:31.030 --> 00:07:32.580
And if we want to
be extra wordy,

00:07:32.580 --> 00:07:35.880
it can be actual or
potential threats

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:40.240
to one's actual or potential
or imagined social connections.

00:07:40.240 --> 00:07:43.050
So it's a pretty
flexible concept.

00:07:43.050 --> 00:07:45.540
But when most people
see this definition,

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:49.030
what you're likely to
think is, oh I get it.

00:07:49.030 --> 00:07:52.650
So people are bothered when
they're socially rejected,

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:54.360
so you're using social pain.

00:07:54.360 --> 00:07:55.710
But that's just a metaphor.

00:07:55.710 --> 00:07:57.720
Social pain is
metaphorical language.

00:07:57.720 --> 00:07:59.254
It's poetic license.

00:07:59.254 --> 00:08:01.170
And so what I want to
take a few minutes to do

00:08:01.170 --> 00:08:03.990
is to think about what it
would take to persuade you

00:08:03.990 --> 00:08:08.550
that social pain is every bit
as much of a real kind of pain

00:08:08.550 --> 00:08:12.360
as when you stub your toe
or when you have a headache,

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:13.800
that from the
brain's perspective

00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:16.950
and from an evolutionary
perspective, social pain

00:08:16.950 --> 00:08:19.214
is very much a
real kind of pain.

00:08:19.214 --> 00:08:21.130
It just manifests in a
slightly different way.

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:25.570
But all physical pains
manifest in different ways.

00:08:25.570 --> 00:08:29.400
So the first thing
that's worth noting

00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:33.690
is that while this may be a
metaphor for social pain--

00:08:33.690 --> 00:08:37.230
and in English, we use language
like "you hurt my feelings"

00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:38.700
and "she broke my heart."

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:40.980
So we use the language
of physical pain

00:08:40.980 --> 00:08:42.809
to talk about social pain.

00:08:42.809 --> 00:08:45.240
And it turns out it's
not just in English.

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:48.625
There was a paper published
years ago-- not by my group--

00:08:48.625 --> 00:08:51.000
showing that in languages all
around the world, including

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:56.250
lots of non-romance languages,
the language of social pain

00:08:56.250 --> 00:08:58.860
is based in the language
of physical pain.

00:08:58.860 --> 00:09:00.214
At least, I assume it is.

00:09:00.214 --> 00:09:02.130
Every once in a while
now, when I get up here,

00:09:02.130 --> 00:09:04.710
I realize I can't
translate most of these.

00:09:04.710 --> 00:09:07.080
But I assume the authors
who wrote this paper could,

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:10.500
and someone would have made them
retract the paper by this point

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:14.460
if they were inaccurate
in their translations.

00:09:14.460 --> 00:09:17.190
So we are neuroimaging folks.

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:18.210
We're neuroscientists.

00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:19.800
And so our approach
is not to look

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:22.260
at how the language is
common around the world,

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:24.460
although I think that's
super interesting.

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:25.980
But instead, we
tend to put people

00:09:25.980 --> 00:09:29.460
in these giant
coffin-like donuts

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:31.290
where you hear
really loud noises.

00:09:31.290 --> 00:09:34.290
It's not a terribly pleasant
place to be-- unless you're me.

00:09:34.290 --> 00:09:37.750
I tend to fall asleep in
scanners when people put me in.

00:09:37.750 --> 00:09:40.620
It's a little bit like being
in the womb, or it's terrible.

00:09:40.620 --> 00:09:42.570
It's one or the other
for most people.

00:09:42.570 --> 00:09:44.160
And we bring folks in.

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:47.250
And this was back in 2001, 2002.

00:09:47.250 --> 00:09:49.200
We brought folks
in, and we had them

00:09:49.200 --> 00:09:53.260
play this silly little ball
tossing game called Cyberball.

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:56.057
And in Cyberball, you're
controlling this hand

00:09:56.057 --> 00:09:56.640
at the bottom.

00:09:56.640 --> 00:09:58.230
If you're the subject
in our scanner,

00:09:58.230 --> 00:09:59.760
you're controlling this hand.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:02.250
And you believe you're playing
with two other real people

00:10:02.250 --> 00:10:06.210
over the internet who are also
laying in scanners right now.

00:10:06.210 --> 00:10:07.900
Of course, we are
social psychologists,

00:10:07.900 --> 00:10:10.050
so we lie to people
all the time about what

00:10:10.050 --> 00:10:11.670
they're doing in the studies.

00:10:11.670 --> 00:10:14.550
And after a few minutes,
the game changes.

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:16.350
And some of you
may now start to be

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:18.810
able to realize how
the game changes.

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:21.960
The other two people, who
are really just code--

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:23.940
they're not people at all--

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:26.700
they stop throwing the
ball to the real subject.

00:10:26.700 --> 00:10:29.030
And this goes on
for a few minutes.

00:10:29.030 --> 00:10:32.040
Subjects get out of the scanner,
and they're usually either kind

00:10:32.040 --> 00:10:33.670
of depressed or angry.

00:10:33.670 --> 00:10:36.210
But they definitely tend to
have a significant emotional

00:10:36.210 --> 00:10:37.930
response to this.

00:10:37.930 --> 00:10:40.470
And so what we
were interested in

00:10:40.470 --> 00:10:42.120
is what was happening
in the brain

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:46.380
while people were being rejected
or excluded from the game

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:49.897
compared to the earlier period
when they had been included.

00:10:49.897 --> 00:10:52.230
These are the brain regions
associated with the distress

00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:53.640
of physical pain.

00:10:53.640 --> 00:10:57.690
So the more bothered you are
by any painful experience

00:10:57.690 --> 00:10:59.640
that you have, the
more activity you're

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:01.825
going to see in
these two regions.

00:11:01.825 --> 00:11:03.450
And when we looked
in the brain at what

00:11:03.450 --> 00:11:06.480
was different between
the people's responses

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:08.820
when they were being excluded
compared to when they were

00:11:08.820 --> 00:11:11.130
included, these were
the only two regions

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:13.990
of the brain that were more
active during rejection

00:11:13.990 --> 00:11:16.095
than when folks were included.

00:11:16.095 --> 00:11:17.970
Moreover, when people
got out of the scanner,

00:11:17.970 --> 00:11:20.760
we asked them to tell
us how painful it

00:11:20.760 --> 00:11:22.830
was to be rejected
while they were

00:11:22.830 --> 00:11:25.450
playing this very boring game.

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:27.450
And the more they
told us they felt

00:11:27.450 --> 00:11:29.100
that it was a
painful experience,

00:11:29.100 --> 00:11:33.780
the more these two regions
showed increasing responses.

00:11:33.780 --> 00:11:37.050
And so this persuades
a fair number of people

00:11:37.050 --> 00:11:39.840
that social pain is
a real kind of pain.

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:43.260
But if it doesn't persuade you,
perhaps the follow-up study

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:43.920
will.

00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:46.800
It turns out that if
you give people Tylenol,

00:11:46.800 --> 00:11:49.070
all these effects go away.

00:11:49.070 --> 00:11:52.130
So the same pain killer that
you take for your headaches

00:11:52.130 --> 00:11:54.650
actually works in some
sense for your heartaches,

00:11:54.650 --> 00:11:57.290
for your sense of being
rejected or excluded.

00:11:57.290 --> 00:11:59.540
It works for that as well.

00:11:59.540 --> 00:12:02.750
Important caveat here--
do not try this at home.

00:12:02.750 --> 00:12:04.710
Tylenol is super toxic.

00:12:04.710 --> 00:12:08.150
500 people a year die
from Tylenol overdoses.

00:12:08.150 --> 00:12:10.860
And so while there are
clinical trials going on

00:12:10.860 --> 00:12:14.480
and we did this, this was done
in a very proper, appropriate

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:15.620
lab-based way.

00:12:15.620 --> 00:12:18.380
Don't do this at home, OK?

00:12:18.380 --> 00:12:19.730
There, I told you not to.

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:22.170
If you do, that's on you now.

00:12:22.170 --> 00:12:27.390
All right, so we have this,
I think, very basic, inborn

00:12:27.390 --> 00:12:31.170
sensitivity to social
rejection that manifests itself

00:12:31.170 --> 00:12:32.160
in the form of pain.

00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:34.350
And it turns out
it's not just humans.

00:12:34.350 --> 00:12:37.260
All mammals show this
kind of response,

00:12:37.260 --> 00:12:40.720
and they tend to show it in
the same regions of the brain.

00:12:40.720 --> 00:12:43.050
So you can look at rats,
you can look at monkeys--

00:12:43.050 --> 00:12:45.466
there are other animals that
have been looked at as well--

00:12:45.466 --> 00:12:47.610
and they tend to show
this same response.

00:12:47.610 --> 00:12:50.000
We have it because
for humans, who

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.440
are born incapable of
taking care of themselves

00:12:52.440 --> 00:12:55.660
when they're infants, you
need a way to stay connected.

00:12:55.660 --> 00:12:58.680
And this makes the
infant and the caregiver

00:12:58.680 --> 00:13:02.219
feel connected and are
very sensitive to distress

00:13:02.219 --> 00:13:02.760
in the other.

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:06.480
Especially the caregiver is very
sensitive to the social pain

00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:08.610
distress calls
given by the infants

00:13:08.610 --> 00:13:10.510
of pretty much any mammals.

00:13:10.510 --> 00:13:12.810
And so the upshot of
this is that social pain

00:13:12.810 --> 00:13:15.330
is one of the things that
motivates us to stay connected,

00:13:15.330 --> 00:13:16.680
to stay together.

00:13:16.680 --> 00:13:19.650
And that allows us to do all
sorts of extraordinary things

00:13:19.650 --> 00:13:22.200
like build buildings
with air conditioning

00:13:22.200 --> 00:13:24.720
and roofs and things like
that that, pretty much,

00:13:24.720 --> 00:13:27.360
if you were on your own and
weren't feeling any motivation

00:13:27.360 --> 00:13:30.390
to connect with other people,
we might never have developed

00:13:30.390 --> 00:13:32.530
these sorts of things.

00:13:32.530 --> 00:13:35.070
Now, on the flip
side of social pain,

00:13:35.070 --> 00:13:36.600
we have social
pleasures, which are

00:13:36.600 --> 00:13:39.790
nicer to think about and
talk about and so on.

00:13:39.790 --> 00:13:43.680
And it turns out that the
same pretty primitive brain

00:13:43.680 --> 00:13:47.850
system that we share with
reptiles and most other animals

00:13:47.850 --> 00:13:51.810
that can walk, the ventral
striatum, the region

00:13:51.810 --> 00:13:53.820
shown in fire here--

00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:55.350
this is a region
that we've known

00:13:55.350 --> 00:13:58.950
for years and years responds
when people in the scanner

00:13:58.950 --> 00:14:01.950
win money, when they
get to eat something

00:14:01.950 --> 00:14:05.880
that's delicious, when they look
at pictures of pretty people.

00:14:05.880 --> 00:14:08.590
All those things
activate this system.

00:14:08.590 --> 00:14:10.890
But it also turns out
we've known for a few years

00:14:10.890 --> 00:14:13.440
now that being liked,
loved, respected,

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:16.620
or even just feeling
understood are all things that

00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:20.910
activate this same system.

00:14:20.910 --> 00:14:23.274
So this is a system
that seems to be just as

00:14:23.274 --> 00:14:24.690
sensitive-- some
evidence suggests

00:14:24.690 --> 00:14:28.380
it's more sensitive to social
rewards than these other kinds

00:14:28.380 --> 00:14:30.750
of rewards that we
tend to think of when

00:14:30.750 --> 00:14:33.970
we think of rewards in general.

00:14:33.970 --> 00:14:36.600
All right, "It's better
to give than to receive."

00:14:36.600 --> 00:14:39.270
You've all heard this
presumably at some point.

00:14:39.270 --> 00:14:40.950
Usually it's
associated with someone

00:14:40.950 --> 00:14:45.840
getting a pretty bad gift
around Christmas or Hanukkah.

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:47.940
Does anyone know who
first said "It's better

00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:50.570
to give than to receive?"

00:14:50.570 --> 00:14:51.860
I'll tell you-- your brain.

00:14:51.860 --> 00:14:54.550
Your brain first said
this because all humans

00:14:54.550 --> 00:14:56.230
are built with this wired in.

00:14:56.230 --> 00:14:58.960
Remember, we started with
the prisoner's dilemma,

00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:02.160
where you can decide to play
selfishly or for the group.

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:05.950
And if you have any strong
views that we are rationally

00:15:05.950 --> 00:15:09.280
self-interest going for the
money kinds of creatures,

00:15:09.280 --> 00:15:12.250
you might imagine that there'd
be social norms suggesting

00:15:12.250 --> 00:15:13.720
that there are
times when we think

00:15:13.720 --> 00:15:16.930
we're supposed to give money to
the group, to work communally.

00:15:16.930 --> 00:15:19.060
You could say that
community condition was just

00:15:19.060 --> 00:15:22.120
people being sensitive to
norms and being afraid of what

00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:24.490
the experimenter would think.

00:15:24.490 --> 00:15:26.710
But if that's the
case, you would still

00:15:26.710 --> 00:15:31.090
expect that the brain's reward
system to respond most strongly

00:15:31.090 --> 00:15:34.060
when people chose to play
the game in the way that

00:15:34.060 --> 00:15:37.720
would, by definition,
maximize their own earnings.

00:15:37.720 --> 00:15:40.380
But that is not what happens
in the prisoner's dilemma.

00:15:40.380 --> 00:15:43.000
In the prisoner's dilemma,
you get the most activity

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.540
in the ventral striatum
when you play communally.

00:15:46.540 --> 00:15:47.701
So this is a case--

00:15:47.701 --> 00:15:49.450
this is a different
kind of social reward.

00:15:49.450 --> 00:15:52.210
The first kind I told you about
is when people tell you they

00:15:52.210 --> 00:15:54.190
like, love, respect you.

00:15:54.190 --> 00:15:57.890
This kind of social reward
is when you do for others.

00:15:57.890 --> 00:15:59.740
And it turns out
that we're built such

00:15:59.740 --> 00:16:03.550
that doing for others is
also a rewarding, pleasurable

00:16:03.550 --> 00:16:05.680
experience, one
that we don't always

00:16:05.680 --> 00:16:07.420
have a very good theory of.

00:16:07.420 --> 00:16:10.630
But it definitely is true.

00:16:10.630 --> 00:16:15.310
Adam Grant, who's at the Wharton
School in Pennsylvania, UPenn--

00:16:15.310 --> 00:16:17.950
he wrote a wonderful
book on the benefits

00:16:17.950 --> 00:16:21.940
of being a giver at
work instead of a taker.

00:16:21.940 --> 00:16:29.060
If you are going to buy one
book this year, well, buy mine.

00:16:29.060 --> 00:16:31.490
But if you're going to buy
two, I would highly, highly

00:16:31.490 --> 00:16:33.689
recommend his book.

00:16:33.689 --> 00:16:35.480
And one of the things
he found in this book

00:16:35.480 --> 00:16:37.688
is that if you go take folks
who are doing relatively

00:16:37.688 --> 00:16:41.030
menial, thankless work, like
working a phone bank trying

00:16:41.030 --> 00:16:44.240
to raise money for scholarships
for the university, where

00:16:44.240 --> 00:16:46.190
everybody is hanging up
and trying to get off

00:16:46.190 --> 00:16:48.650
the phone with you,
and you bring someone

00:16:48.650 --> 00:16:50.720
in who won one of
their scholarships

00:16:50.720 --> 00:16:53.810
that they're raising money
for who then tells some

00:16:53.810 --> 00:16:57.470
of these phone bank folks about
how the work they're doing

00:16:57.470 --> 00:17:00.340
actually tangibly
benefits someone,

00:17:00.340 --> 00:17:03.984
the productivity of these
folks goes through the roof.

00:17:03.984 --> 00:17:05.650
And when I say it
goes through the roof,

00:17:05.650 --> 00:17:07.192
I don't mean that
day or the next day

00:17:07.192 --> 00:17:09.775
where you would expect them to
be like, oh, that was so great.

00:17:09.775 --> 00:17:11.839
That was fun that we heard
from that 20-year-old

00:17:11.839 --> 00:17:14.635
telling us what this
award meant for them.

00:17:14.635 --> 00:17:16.760
It's a month later that
they come back and measure.

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:18.650
And a month later,
the productivity

00:17:18.650 --> 00:17:20.540
of the folks who got
this intervention

00:17:20.540 --> 00:17:21.650
is dramatically higher.

00:17:21.650 --> 00:17:23.450
And this has been
replicated several times

00:17:23.450 --> 00:17:27.180
in different contexts, so
I think it's really legit.

00:17:27.180 --> 00:17:31.410
So humans are sensitive to
social pain, social pleasure.

00:17:31.410 --> 00:17:33.780
You would think that if these
are things that can really

00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:35.790
move around our
well-being, we might

00:17:35.790 --> 00:17:37.980
have a system in
our brain that helps

00:17:37.980 --> 00:17:40.410
us navigate the social
world so that we

00:17:40.410 --> 00:17:42.270
can maximize our
social pleasures

00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:44.550
and minimize the social pains.

00:17:44.550 --> 00:17:46.740
For some time, people
thought that it

00:17:46.740 --> 00:17:50.400
was the basic analytical
system in the brain, which

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:52.620
is shown here in green--

00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:54.582
loosely shown here in green.

00:17:54.582 --> 00:17:56.040
These are systems
that are involved

00:17:56.040 --> 00:17:59.070
in math and logical reasoning
and accounting and working

00:17:59.070 --> 00:18:02.340
memory, holding things
temporarily in mind.

00:18:02.340 --> 00:18:04.140
But it turns out
that there really

00:18:04.140 --> 00:18:06.660
is a completely
separate network that's

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:09.660
involved in our social
thinking that doesn't really

00:18:09.660 --> 00:18:13.202
overlap with the network for
analytical thinking at all.

00:18:13.202 --> 00:18:14.910
And we've learned some
interesting things

00:18:14.910 --> 00:18:15.930
about this network.

00:18:15.930 --> 00:18:17.610
One of the things
we've learned is

00:18:17.610 --> 00:18:19.680
that these two networks--
the social thinking

00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:22.200
and analytical thinking
networks-- kind of operate

00:18:22.200 --> 00:18:26.520
like a neural seesaw, where
activity in one going up

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:29.190
tends to be associated with
activity in the other going

00:18:29.190 --> 00:18:30.840
down and vise versa.

00:18:30.840 --> 00:18:32.960
They seem to trade
off of each other.

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:34.740
And we can think
immediately about how

00:18:34.740 --> 00:18:37.590
that might be relevant
in the workplace, right?

00:18:37.590 --> 00:18:39.960
I assume Google,
like most companies,

00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:43.800
really prioritizes people being
highly analytically skilled

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:46.560
many, many hours of the day.

00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:49.920
And the goal is to
just emphasize that

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:53.760
without necessarily detracting
from other capacities

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:54.841
that we might have.

00:18:54.841 --> 00:18:56.340
But there's some
evidence to suggest

00:18:56.340 --> 00:18:58.215
that if you're putting
the pedal to the metal

00:18:58.215 --> 00:19:01.410
on the analytical side, that may
come at a real cost of actually

00:19:01.410 --> 00:19:05.760
dampening down some
of our social skills

00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:08.130
and our ability to
detect certain things

00:19:08.130 --> 00:19:12.010
socially in others in
our social environment.

00:19:12.010 --> 00:19:15.220
Another thing we've learned
is sort of a funny result,

00:19:15.220 --> 00:19:17.320
and I'll show it
to you this way.

00:19:17.320 --> 00:19:19.360
So let's say I brought
you into my scanner.

00:19:19.360 --> 00:19:20.200
It's not my scanner.

00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:21.570
It's UCLA's scanner.

00:19:21.570 --> 00:19:24.990
I brought you in, and I told
you that what you're going to do

00:19:24.990 --> 00:19:25.920
is lay in the scanner.

00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:27.790
And you're going to
do math for a minute,

00:19:27.790 --> 00:19:29.520
and then you're going to
lay there and rest and do

00:19:29.520 --> 00:19:32.040
nothing for a minute, and then
math for a minute and rest.

00:19:32.040 --> 00:19:33.210
And the math is super easy.

00:19:33.210 --> 00:19:34.950
It's like 3 plus 4 type math.

00:19:34.950 --> 00:19:36.510
And the rest is nothing.

00:19:36.510 --> 00:19:38.760
And this time, even though
I'm a social psychologist,

00:19:38.760 --> 00:19:39.780
I'm not lying to you.

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:41.460
This is exactly what
you do while you're

00:19:41.460 --> 00:19:42.940
laying in the scanner.

00:19:42.940 --> 00:19:46.110
And so we can go look at these
analytical parts of the brain,

00:19:46.110 --> 00:19:48.780
and they will do just what
we would expect them to do.

00:19:48.780 --> 00:19:50.110
They'll do something like this.

00:19:50.110 --> 00:19:52.260
This is idealized, but
something like this.

00:19:52.260 --> 00:19:55.140
When you're doing math, the
analytical parts light up.

00:19:55.140 --> 00:19:57.420
And when you're
resting, they quiet down

00:19:57.420 --> 00:20:00.180
because you don't need
them to rest and do nothing

00:20:00.180 --> 00:20:02.050
while you're laying
in the scanner.

00:20:02.050 --> 00:20:04.352
Now, we can look at
the same exact task

00:20:04.352 --> 00:20:06.060
and what's happening
in the social brain,

00:20:06.060 --> 00:20:08.100
in the social thinking network.

00:20:08.100 --> 00:20:10.530
Well, what we would
expect to see is this--

00:20:10.530 --> 00:20:12.030
not much at all.

00:20:12.030 --> 00:20:14.209
Because you don't need your
social brain to do math.

00:20:14.209 --> 00:20:16.500
In fact, if you activate your
social brain while you're

00:20:16.500 --> 00:20:18.320
doing math, it interferes.

00:20:18.320 --> 00:20:21.120
And you don't need your
social brain during rest.

00:20:21.120 --> 00:20:22.920
So that's what
we'd expect to see.

00:20:22.920 --> 00:20:25.470
But what you
actually see is this.

00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:30.570
So the social brain comes on
incredibly reliably any time

00:20:30.570 --> 00:20:32.400
there is a break in the action.

00:20:32.400 --> 00:20:35.130
And it comes on within a
few hundred milliseconds

00:20:35.130 --> 00:20:38.577
of finishing any sort of
cognitive, goal-directed task.

00:20:38.577 --> 00:20:41.160
So there are folks who have done
things with depth electrodes.

00:20:41.160 --> 00:20:42.951
They put them right in
the right positions,

00:20:42.951 --> 00:20:45.390
and they can tell within
300 milliseconds--

00:20:45.390 --> 00:20:47.670
it's actually a guy
at Stanford nearby--

00:20:47.670 --> 00:20:50.130
that within 300 milliseconds,
the social brain

00:20:50.130 --> 00:20:54.190
pops back on whenever there's
a break in the action.

00:20:54.190 --> 00:20:57.880
And so we can ask ourselves,
well, why would that happen?

00:20:57.880 --> 00:21:03.270
And while I'm not going to
spend lots of time in my lecture

00:21:03.270 --> 00:21:08.950
today going over
why that happens,

00:21:08.950 --> 00:21:12.330
what I can tell you is that the
summary result from our studies

00:21:12.330 --> 00:21:15.420
is that to the extent that
you spontaneously activate

00:21:15.420 --> 00:21:18.270
this network in short
periods of downtime

00:21:18.270 --> 00:21:21.990
in between more significant
events in your life,

00:21:21.990 --> 00:21:26.040
if the next thing you have to
do involves social thinking,

00:21:26.040 --> 00:21:28.320
you're better prepared for it.

00:21:28.320 --> 00:21:30.930
You actually perform
better on social tasks

00:21:30.930 --> 00:21:32.430
where you have to
think about what's

00:21:32.430 --> 00:21:35.400
going on in the minds of
other folks to the extent

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:39.030
that this network has
spontaneously activated itself.

00:21:39.030 --> 00:21:41.820
And what that suggests is
that evolution has essentially

00:21:41.820 --> 00:21:43.860
made a bet that the
best thing to do

00:21:43.860 --> 00:21:46.890
with our spare
cycles in our brain

00:21:46.890 --> 00:21:51.240
as we have downtime is to get
ready for thinking socially,

00:21:51.240 --> 00:21:54.140
that that is really
evolutionarily significant.

00:21:54.140 --> 00:21:56.640
Because this is pretty much the
only thing in the brain that

00:21:56.640 --> 00:21:59.340
has this sort of pattern, where
every time there's a break

00:21:59.340 --> 00:22:03.270
and we can reset, it resets
towards the social domain.

00:22:03.270 --> 00:22:06.330
We actually have a lot of
data that speaks to that now.

00:22:06.330 --> 00:22:08.944
And so in essence,
what that does for us--

00:22:08.944 --> 00:22:10.860
and I think this is
really, really important--

00:22:10.860 --> 00:22:13.330
is that when we look
out into the world,

00:22:13.330 --> 00:22:16.980
we could see all of this
just as physical objects

00:22:16.980 --> 00:22:19.370
in physical motion.

00:22:19.370 --> 00:22:21.870
We could describe it all in
terms of physics and mechanics

00:22:21.870 --> 00:22:22.900
and so on.

00:22:22.900 --> 00:22:25.199
But most people-- the
vast majority of people--

00:22:25.199 --> 00:22:26.740
when they look at
this, what they see

00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:28.360
has psychological meaning.

00:22:28.360 --> 00:22:31.570
They see people having thoughts,
feelings, interactions,

00:22:31.570 --> 00:22:33.440
intentions.

00:22:33.440 --> 00:22:36.490
And this tendency to
turn on this network

00:22:36.490 --> 00:22:39.010
as we walk into
each new experience

00:22:39.010 --> 00:22:41.530
is something that
prepares us to see

00:22:41.530 --> 00:22:44.170
the world in a
psychological fashion

00:22:44.170 --> 00:22:48.670
rather than in a physics-based,
mechanical fashion.

00:22:48.670 --> 00:22:53.470
So that's a very short course
on some of the evidence that

00:22:53.470 --> 00:22:57.790
suggests that we really do
have some basic social features

00:22:57.790 --> 00:23:00.340
to us and that we are not
purely self-interested.

00:23:00.340 --> 00:23:03.010
We are not just Homo economicus.

00:23:03.010 --> 00:23:05.590
We are that but not just that.

00:23:05.590 --> 00:23:07.780
Of course, I could have
skipped those 20 minutes

00:23:07.780 --> 00:23:11.110
and just showed you the quote
from Albert Einstein where

00:23:11.110 --> 00:23:13.090
he says, "Man owes his
strength in the struggle

00:23:13.090 --> 00:23:16.720
for existence to the fact
that he is a social animal."

00:23:16.720 --> 00:23:20.200
But, you know, then I would
have no job being here at all.

00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:21.930
I could've just
showed you that slide.

00:23:21.930 --> 00:23:24.400
So I'm going to spend a
few minutes telling you now

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:29.590
about how some of these things
relate to business directly,

00:23:29.590 --> 00:23:32.227
and then I'm going to turn
to what we're doing now

00:23:32.227 --> 00:23:34.060
with a different kind
of neuroscience that's

00:23:34.060 --> 00:23:34.851
more work-relevant.

00:23:34.851 --> 00:23:37.720
And I'm pretty excited
to get to that.

00:23:37.720 --> 00:23:40.810
OK, so in any workplace,
in any business,

00:23:40.810 --> 00:23:43.180
you're off trying to hire folks.

00:23:43.180 --> 00:23:45.010
And it's been a long
time, now, that we've

00:23:45.010 --> 00:23:47.230
understood that the
goal of hiring folks

00:23:47.230 --> 00:23:49.720
is to accrue the most talent.

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:52.120
So any HR department
is out there

00:23:52.120 --> 00:23:56.200
trying to find the individuals
who are A-plus people.

00:23:56.200 --> 00:23:58.060
And the A-plus
people are the people

00:23:58.060 --> 00:24:01.270
with the highest IQs, the
most training and experience,

00:24:01.270 --> 00:24:02.980
who went to the best schools.

00:24:02.980 --> 00:24:05.117
And norms about these
things change over time,

00:24:05.117 --> 00:24:06.700
but that's roughly
speaking describing

00:24:06.700 --> 00:24:09.580
what's happened over the
last couple of decades

00:24:09.580 --> 00:24:11.812
in terms of how we
try to acquire people.

00:24:11.812 --> 00:24:13.270
And the goal is to
make sure, then,

00:24:13.270 --> 00:24:16.480
that your company has
the most human capital.

00:24:16.480 --> 00:24:18.465
It's almost like a sort
of role-playing game

00:24:18.465 --> 00:24:19.840
where you're trying
to get people

00:24:19.840 --> 00:24:24.010
with the most intellectual and
academic skills for performing

00:24:24.010 --> 00:24:26.500
the feats they will
need to do at work.

00:24:26.500 --> 00:24:30.130
Some economists looked
at this and discovered

00:24:30.130 --> 00:24:31.960
that if you want to
see the relationship

00:24:31.960 --> 00:24:35.350
between human capital and
the company's bottom line,

00:24:35.350 --> 00:24:38.620
the vast majority
of that relationship

00:24:38.620 --> 00:24:42.640
is actually explained by the
links between the individuals

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:43.811
in the company.

00:24:43.811 --> 00:24:45.310
And so here what
we're talking about

00:24:45.310 --> 00:24:48.460
is not human capital but social
capital, the extent to which

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:52.900
a company makes the boundaries
between people and sections

00:24:52.900 --> 00:24:55.780
of the company permeable so
that they can connect easily

00:24:55.780 --> 00:24:56.770
with each other.

00:24:56.770 --> 00:24:58.300
And what's critical
about this is

00:24:58.300 --> 00:25:01.120
you've got this A-plus person
down here with some special set

00:25:01.120 --> 00:25:02.080
of skills.

00:25:02.080 --> 00:25:03.580
And if they're
siloed and they don't

00:25:03.580 --> 00:25:05.690
feel really connected
to other folks,

00:25:05.690 --> 00:25:07.330
well, that person
up there is never

00:25:07.330 --> 00:25:09.880
going to benefit from their
skills when they could

00:25:09.880 --> 00:25:10.700
and vise versa.

00:25:10.700 --> 00:25:13.420
This person is not going
to easily seek them out

00:25:13.420 --> 00:25:17.300
because they don't have an easy
path to get access to them.

00:25:17.300 --> 00:25:20.650
So it's important to build this
kind of social capital purely

00:25:20.650 --> 00:25:23.280
for economic reasons
at companies.

00:25:23.280 --> 00:25:26.030
Here's another version
of something similar.

00:25:26.030 --> 00:25:30.550
So this is a phone bank
company, I think, in Germany.

00:25:30.550 --> 00:25:33.580
And the company Humanyze, who
does the badge testing where

00:25:33.580 --> 00:25:36.490
it tracks your every
movement throughout the day--

00:25:36.490 --> 00:25:39.760
they did a study
with this company.

00:25:39.760 --> 00:25:42.310
And the way the company was
working when they showed up

00:25:42.310 --> 00:25:45.070
is that there'd be five or six
people in a phone bank that

00:25:45.070 --> 00:25:46.780
were in a pod together.

00:25:46.780 --> 00:25:49.570
And they would get their
15 minute breaks staggered,

00:25:49.570 --> 00:25:52.450
so they all took their
breaks at different times.

00:25:52.450 --> 00:25:55.000
And Humanyze came in and said,
hey, why don't you give them

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:56.650
their breaks together?

00:25:56.650 --> 00:25:58.780
Because if you give them
their breaks together,

00:25:58.780 --> 00:26:00.700
they'll actually be
more socially connected

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:03.580
to one another and actually
feel like they're on a team.

00:26:03.580 --> 00:26:07.397
Now, this seems like a
really small difference.

00:26:07.397 --> 00:26:08.980
But it turned out
that this difference

00:26:08.980 --> 00:26:11.560
had really significant
effects on the extent

00:26:11.560 --> 00:26:13.990
to which people at the
company felt cohesive

00:26:13.990 --> 00:26:15.880
with the other people
they worked with,

00:26:15.880 --> 00:26:19.130
the productivity they had,
the stress levels they had.

00:26:19.130 --> 00:26:21.160
So these simple
changes where they're

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:24.790
being sensitive to enhancing
the social dynamics of the group

00:26:24.790 --> 00:26:26.200
had really substantial effects.

00:26:26.200 --> 00:26:28.199
And they've done other
studies like this as well

00:26:28.199 --> 00:26:30.220
and tend to see something.

00:26:30.220 --> 00:26:34.030
If nobody is focusing on the
social aspects of a company,

00:26:34.030 --> 00:26:35.620
that becomes low-hanging fruit.

00:26:35.620 --> 00:26:38.050
Because nobody's actually gone
after the low-hanging fruit

00:26:38.050 --> 00:26:38.590
before.

00:26:38.590 --> 00:26:41.590
And this is, I think,
that sort of thing.

00:26:41.590 --> 00:26:44.060
We can think about
performance feedback.

00:26:44.060 --> 00:26:46.324
Everybody gets performance
feedback at most companies.

00:26:46.324 --> 00:26:48.490
There's a few companies
that have done away with it.

00:26:48.490 --> 00:26:49.780
It's hard to do away with it.

00:26:49.780 --> 00:26:52.270
You want your employees
to get feedback,

00:26:52.270 --> 00:26:56.030
but nobody likes getting
performance feedback.

00:26:56.030 --> 00:26:57.850
And so for me, one of
the things I always

00:26:57.850 --> 00:27:00.520
think about when I think
about performance feedback

00:27:00.520 --> 00:27:02.650
is that for the person
giving the feedback,

00:27:02.650 --> 00:27:04.360
they're just giving
constructive advice

00:27:04.360 --> 00:27:07.060
for how you can go be more
efficient and effective.

00:27:07.060 --> 00:27:08.980
And for the person
receiving the feedback,

00:27:08.980 --> 00:27:11.170
it's like somebody's
punching you in the face--

00:27:11.170 --> 00:27:14.320
typically, unless you're
the golden child of whatever

00:27:14.320 --> 00:27:15.760
company you're working at.

00:27:15.760 --> 00:27:17.620
And so we have a way
of understanding that.

00:27:17.620 --> 00:27:19.870
So we've talked
about social pain,

00:27:19.870 --> 00:27:22.210
and the idea is that
if we think of this

00:27:22.210 --> 00:27:24.910
as a genuinely painful
event for people

00:27:24.910 --> 00:27:28.570
to be told information that
may make you feel less valued

00:27:28.570 --> 00:27:31.130
and worthy at the company
that you're working at,

00:27:31.130 --> 00:27:33.130
then it's weird to think
that those folks should

00:27:33.130 --> 00:27:35.620
be able to just go back
to work and be effective.

00:27:35.620 --> 00:27:38.320
We wouldn't expect
someone to break their leg

00:27:38.320 --> 00:27:39.400
and then go back to work.

00:27:39.400 --> 00:27:41.590
We'd say, go get
that taken care of

00:27:41.590 --> 00:27:46.420
and come back to work when
it's all in a cast and feeling

00:27:46.420 --> 00:27:47.320
better.

00:27:47.320 --> 00:27:50.890
There's work that shows
that after people have been

00:27:50.890 --> 00:27:55.690
rejected, their IQs
go down significantly

00:27:55.690 --> 00:27:57.490
and their performance
on standardized tests

00:27:57.490 --> 00:28:00.610
like the GREs plummet--

00:28:00.610 --> 00:28:06.110
68% if you've just been accepted
and made to feel good, 39%

00:28:06.110 --> 00:28:08.170
if you've just been rejected.

00:28:08.170 --> 00:28:09.790
So after you've
just been rejected,

00:28:09.790 --> 00:28:11.410
don't go take the GREs.

00:28:11.410 --> 00:28:12.910
You will not do well.

00:28:12.910 --> 00:28:14.200
It's not a good solution.

00:28:14.200 --> 00:28:16.660
Eat some ice cream.

00:28:16.660 --> 00:28:19.510
We can think more
directly about happiness

00:28:19.510 --> 00:28:22.360
and how to promote that.

00:28:22.360 --> 00:28:25.570
We know, of course, that two
of the major factors that drive

00:28:25.570 --> 00:28:29.290
happiness are money and health.

00:28:29.290 --> 00:28:30.967
So let's start with health.

00:28:30.967 --> 00:28:32.800
So we all know smoking's
bad for you, right?

00:28:32.800 --> 00:28:34.841
In California, almost
nobody ever smokes anymore.

00:28:34.841 --> 00:28:38.110
But in most of the world,
lots of people still smoke.

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:42.040
You can look at the
morbidity statistics

00:28:42.040 --> 00:28:44.350
for your likelihood
of essentially dying

00:28:44.350 --> 00:28:46.800
from different
kinds of behaviors,

00:28:46.800 --> 00:28:49.960
from not being physically
active, being obese,

00:28:49.960 --> 00:28:51.250
having pneumonia.

00:28:51.250 --> 00:28:54.940
And smoking's like the
worst one from behaviors

00:28:54.940 --> 00:28:57.190
that you can
personally engage in.

00:28:57.190 --> 00:28:58.399
Smoking's really, really bad.

00:28:58.399 --> 00:29:00.314
And that's one of the
reasons we spend about a

00:29:00.314 --> 00:29:02.500
half billion dollars a
year in the United States

00:29:02.500 --> 00:29:06.130
to stop people from smoking and
to get people to stop smoking

00:29:06.130 --> 00:29:07.960
once they have started.

00:29:07.960 --> 00:29:09.530
But what I haven't
shown you here,

00:29:09.530 --> 00:29:12.190
which is the most interesting
part of the chart,

00:29:12.190 --> 00:29:15.340
is that it actually turns
out that not cultivating

00:29:15.340 --> 00:29:17.860
a meaningful social
group is actually

00:29:17.860 --> 00:29:19.990
more dangerous to your
health than smoking

00:29:19.990 --> 00:29:22.610
15 cigarettes a day.

00:29:22.610 --> 00:29:26.530
So while health is super
important for your well-being,

00:29:26.530 --> 00:29:28.630
it turns out that being
socially connected

00:29:28.630 --> 00:29:34.420
is also super important
for your well-being.

00:29:34.420 --> 00:29:36.700
We know people
value being wealthy.

00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:38.650
We know people value
material wealth.

00:29:38.650 --> 00:29:40.660
The percentage of
people who value it

00:29:40.660 --> 00:29:43.630
has gone up and up
in the United States.

00:29:43.630 --> 00:29:47.690
And I value it too, so I'm not
really throwing stones at all.

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:51.160
But what I will say is that this
seems largely to be a mistake.

00:29:51.160 --> 00:29:53.620
Because as wealth rises,
happiness typically

00:29:53.620 --> 00:29:55.150
doesn't change at all.

00:29:55.150 --> 00:29:57.700
And you can cut the data
a million different ways.

00:29:57.700 --> 00:30:00.610
Unless you're moving
people from genuine poverty

00:30:00.610 --> 00:30:02.050
to out of poverty--

00:30:02.050 --> 00:30:04.750
then every dollar really
does change happiness

00:30:04.750 --> 00:30:05.620
and well-being.

00:30:05.620 --> 00:30:07.420
But once you hit a
certain threshold,

00:30:07.420 --> 00:30:10.750
you get very diminishing
returns for increasing money.

00:30:10.750 --> 00:30:12.457
So what makes people happier?

00:30:12.457 --> 00:30:14.290
Well, the people who
report being very happy

00:30:14.290 --> 00:30:18.970
are the people who spend lots
of time with friends and family.

00:30:18.970 --> 00:30:24.040
Some economists looked
at this using money

00:30:24.040 --> 00:30:25.900
as a sort of comparison point.

00:30:25.900 --> 00:30:29.950
And they said, OK, how much does
spending an extra hour a week

00:30:29.950 --> 00:30:32.470
with someone you really like,
going to get coffee with them

00:30:32.470 --> 00:30:33.620
or something like that--

00:30:33.620 --> 00:30:35.650
how much does that
increase your happiness?

00:30:35.650 --> 00:30:37.270
And they put it
in terms of money.

00:30:37.270 --> 00:30:39.280
They said, how much
money would you

00:30:39.280 --> 00:30:41.630
have to make extra
in a given year

00:30:41.630 --> 00:30:43.630
in order to get the same
amount of happiness you

00:30:43.630 --> 00:30:47.680
get from spending an hour
a week with a good friend?

00:30:47.680 --> 00:30:50.200
It turns out it's a
giant amount of money.

00:30:50.200 --> 00:30:52.870
You have to make an
extra $100,000 a year

00:30:52.870 --> 00:30:54.670
to get the same increase
in your happiness

00:30:54.670 --> 00:30:56.562
as spending an hour
with someone you like.

00:30:56.562 --> 00:30:58.270
You get to pick the
person you're talking

00:30:58.270 --> 00:30:59.890
about here, someone you like.

00:30:59.890 --> 00:31:01.930
Which of these is
more fun, working

00:31:01.930 --> 00:31:05.290
to make an extra hundred grand
or spending time with a friend?

00:31:05.290 --> 00:31:08.944
And as we do this, we
have less time to do this.

00:31:08.944 --> 00:31:10.360
These are the
choices we all make.

00:31:10.360 --> 00:31:12.730
We move cross-country
for job opportunities

00:31:12.730 --> 00:31:16.090
and leave our social
networks behind.

00:31:16.090 --> 00:31:18.790
We can think about this within
the workplace specifically,

00:31:18.790 --> 00:31:22.580
not just having friends in life
but having friends at work.

00:31:22.580 --> 00:31:25.330
It turns out that
while people who

00:31:25.330 --> 00:31:27.700
love the company
they work at often

00:31:27.700 --> 00:31:30.490
say it's because they love the
interesting and challenging

00:31:30.490 --> 00:31:33.010
work they do there,
they also often say

00:31:33.010 --> 00:31:35.920
their number one reason for
loving the company they work at

00:31:35.920 --> 00:31:39.640
is the co-workers that
they get to work with.

00:31:39.640 --> 00:31:43.150
And people who say, I have
a best friend at work--

00:31:43.150 --> 00:31:45.820
people who answer yes to this--
the divisions of companies

00:31:45.820 --> 00:31:49.450
they work in tend to have
customers who are happier,

00:31:49.450 --> 00:31:55.010
they're more productive, and
they show greater profit.

00:31:55.010 --> 00:31:58.750
So the upshot of this-- and then
I'm going to turn to my last

00:31:58.750 --> 00:31:59.710
piece--

00:31:59.710 --> 00:32:02.800
is that in the
workplace, we tend

00:32:02.800 --> 00:32:04.630
to think that this
is the primary way

00:32:04.630 --> 00:32:07.034
to incentivize people.

00:32:07.034 --> 00:32:08.950
When you look at all the
incentive structures,

00:32:08.950 --> 00:32:10.408
they almost always
either come down

00:32:10.408 --> 00:32:14.020
to current or future promised
money in one form or another.

00:32:14.020 --> 00:32:15.640
Health plans are
just money that are

00:32:15.640 --> 00:32:19.370
being spent for you in a
certain other material way.

00:32:19.370 --> 00:32:22.840
And the point is that
we have some needs

00:32:22.840 --> 00:32:25.480
that money are really,
really good at covering.

00:32:25.480 --> 00:32:27.250
So if you go to
Maslow's hierarchy--

00:32:27.250 --> 00:32:30.050
and this is a simplified
form with physical, social,

00:32:30.050 --> 00:32:31.330
and meaning needs--

00:32:31.330 --> 00:32:34.160
physical needs are pretty
well handled with money.

00:32:34.160 --> 00:32:35.950
But the other two aren't at all.

00:32:35.950 --> 00:32:38.680
And so again, these
become low-hanging fruit.

00:32:38.680 --> 00:32:41.380
If nobody is
incentivizing anyone

00:32:41.380 --> 00:32:43.540
with these other
approaches, then they

00:32:43.540 --> 00:32:46.000
become a really
effective way for you

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:48.580
to make that kind of
difference in whatever group

00:32:48.580 --> 00:32:49.780
you're working in.

00:32:49.780 --> 00:32:52.930
OK, so last chunk of what
I'm going to talk about

00:32:52.930 --> 00:32:55.870
is what I think one of the
big parts of the future

00:32:55.870 --> 00:32:57.730
of social neuroscience
is, and it's

00:32:57.730 --> 00:33:01.000
going to have a big
connection to the workplace

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:07.180
and not just be in the ivory
tower where I tend to work.

00:33:07.180 --> 00:33:10.210
This kind of work
involves getting away

00:33:10.210 --> 00:33:13.780
from giant, heavy MRI
scanners and getting

00:33:13.780 --> 00:33:17.620
to lightweight, portable,
mobile neuroimaging technologies

00:33:17.620 --> 00:33:22.240
like functional near-infrared
spectroscopy, or fNIRS.

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:26.260
MRIs depend on differences
in the magnetic properties

00:33:26.260 --> 00:33:29.430
of oxygenated and
deoxygenated hemoglobin.

00:33:29.430 --> 00:33:31.840
fNIRS is kind of
the same, except it

00:33:31.840 --> 00:33:34.060
depends on the light
absorption properties that

00:33:34.060 --> 00:33:36.460
differ between those
two types of blood.

00:33:36.460 --> 00:33:39.310
It's basically just the same
thing as the pulse oximeter

00:33:39.310 --> 00:33:42.190
you wear on your finger
when you go to the doctors,

00:33:42.190 --> 00:33:44.410
except it's all over your brain.

00:33:44.410 --> 00:33:47.900
And it's super
portable and mobile.

00:33:47.900 --> 00:33:49.480
So you can put--

00:33:49.480 --> 00:33:52.090
you're basically putting
a very small computer

00:33:52.090 --> 00:33:54.850
and a sizable battery in a
backpack, which you can either

00:33:54.850 --> 00:33:57.280
wear or put on the table
behind the subject.

00:33:57.280 --> 00:33:59.200
It doesn't have to
actually be on your back.

00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:01.810
But it allows you to
be flexible in where

00:34:01.810 --> 00:34:04.374
you do your research
and the kind of research

00:34:04.374 --> 00:34:06.040
that you can now do
that you could never

00:34:06.040 --> 00:34:07.900
do with an MRI scanner.

00:34:07.900 --> 00:34:09.230
And it has downsides as well.

00:34:09.230 --> 00:34:10.219
There's no question.

00:34:10.219 --> 00:34:12.880
It doesn't have the same
spatial resolution as MRI.

00:34:12.880 --> 00:34:15.310
And currently, it doesn't
penetrate very deep

00:34:15.310 --> 00:34:16.040
into the brain.

00:34:16.040 --> 00:34:17.949
So it gets you the
cortical surface.

00:34:17.949 --> 00:34:20.420
But I think in the next
five to seven years,

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:24.050
that's probably going to
change a fair bit as well.

00:34:24.050 --> 00:34:26.440
So the first thing we did
when we decided to test out

00:34:26.440 --> 00:34:28.210
this equipment was
we wanted to go

00:34:28.210 --> 00:34:31.429
replicate something we had done
in our lab over and over again.

00:34:31.429 --> 00:34:33.802
So there's this paradigm
that Emily Falk,

00:34:33.802 --> 00:34:35.260
one of my former
graduate students,

00:34:35.260 --> 00:34:38.560
and I developed, where we try
to persuade people while they're

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:39.639
laying in the scanner.

00:34:39.639 --> 00:34:43.000
And then we ask them
later and track them

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:46.150
in various ways using wrist
trackers and other things

00:34:46.150 --> 00:34:49.719
to see how much they've actually
changed their behavior in line

00:34:49.719 --> 00:34:52.030
with whatever we were
trying to persuade them of--

00:34:52.030 --> 00:34:54.679
to use sunscreen
more, to stop smoking,

00:34:54.679 --> 00:34:57.580
to get more physical
exercise, to sleep more.

00:34:57.580 --> 00:35:00.920
We do lots of public health
types of things like that.

00:35:00.920 --> 00:35:03.040
And it turns out that
when you see activity

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:05.200
in this medial prefrontal
region here that's

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:06.580
shown in yellow there--

00:35:06.580 --> 00:35:09.070
when that goes up when people
are seeing the messages,

00:35:09.070 --> 00:35:11.230
people tend to then
change their behavior

00:35:11.230 --> 00:35:13.036
in message-consistent ways.

00:35:13.036 --> 00:35:14.410
We think this has
something to do

00:35:14.410 --> 00:35:16.750
with basically adopting
and integrating

00:35:16.750 --> 00:35:18.942
the message into your identity.

00:35:18.942 --> 00:35:20.650
Because this is a
region that's very much

00:35:20.650 --> 00:35:24.220
associated with
self-processes and valuation.

00:35:24.220 --> 00:35:26.450
So we think-- but we
don't know for sure--

00:35:26.450 --> 00:35:29.000
that that seems to be part
of what's going on there.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:32.380
On the flip side, when people
are resistant to a persuasive

00:35:32.380 --> 00:35:34.630
message and they're internally
counter-arguing saying,

00:35:34.630 --> 00:35:36.370
this is stupid because--

00:35:36.370 --> 00:35:39.400
you see more activity in the
right dorsolateral prefrontal

00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:43.310
cortex, and you'll see less
behavior change over time.

00:35:43.310 --> 00:35:47.530
So we did the same thing in
our first study with fNIRS,

00:35:47.530 --> 00:35:49.420
and we basically found
the exact same result.

00:35:49.420 --> 00:35:51.340
We were actually pretty
shocked that we found this.

00:35:51.340 --> 00:35:53.506
We thought maybe we'd get
a little bit of something,

00:35:53.506 --> 00:35:54.410
but there it is.

00:35:54.410 --> 00:35:56.140
So this is showing--

00:35:56.140 --> 00:35:57.370
to us, at least--

00:35:57.370 --> 00:36:01.480
that we can do something
analogous with fNIRS

00:36:01.480 --> 00:36:03.700
that we've been doing for
years and years with fMRI

00:36:03.700 --> 00:36:05.510
and we had a lot
of confidence in.

00:36:05.510 --> 00:36:08.710
But fNIRS has the ability
to do so much more

00:36:08.710 --> 00:36:10.474
than just replicate
what we've been

00:36:10.474 --> 00:36:11.890
able to do while
people are laying

00:36:11.890 --> 00:36:14.060
on their back in the scanner.

00:36:14.060 --> 00:36:17.710
And this often
involves an approach

00:36:17.710 --> 00:36:19.072
called neural synchrony.

00:36:19.072 --> 00:36:20.530
There's other names
for it as well,

00:36:20.530 --> 00:36:22.070
but I call it neural synchrony.

00:36:22.070 --> 00:36:25.150
And the basic idea is you
go to the same spot in two

00:36:25.150 --> 00:36:28.610
different people's brains as
they're experiencing something,

00:36:28.610 --> 00:36:33.140
and you look at how the activity
there fluctuates over time.

00:36:33.140 --> 00:36:35.860
And to the extent that two
people in the same spot

00:36:35.860 --> 00:36:39.730
in their brains are watching a
video or having a conversation

00:36:39.730 --> 00:36:43.030
and they're fluctuations
are fluctuating together,

00:36:43.030 --> 00:36:44.450
that's neural synchrony.

00:36:44.450 --> 00:36:47.030
And if they're doing
random different things,

00:36:47.030 --> 00:36:49.130
there is no synchrony
in that case.

00:36:49.130 --> 00:36:51.700
And it turns out-- and I'll
show you data to back this up

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:52.590
in a minute--

00:36:52.590 --> 00:36:54.940
that what this really
tends to get at

00:36:54.940 --> 00:36:57.940
is whether two people
aren't literally just

00:36:57.940 --> 00:37:00.880
being exposed to the same
thing but are sharing

00:37:00.880 --> 00:37:02.170
the same experience of it.

00:37:02.170 --> 00:37:03.970
They're experiencing
it and having

00:37:03.970 --> 00:37:06.790
the same kind of
understanding and perspective

00:37:06.790 --> 00:37:08.284
on what's going on.

00:37:08.284 --> 00:37:09.700
But first, I want
to show you what

00:37:09.700 --> 00:37:12.380
neural synchrony looks like.

00:37:12.380 --> 00:37:16.900
So these are the
results of two people--

00:37:16.900 --> 00:37:18.430
these are their brains--

00:37:18.430 --> 00:37:20.570
watching a fighter pilot video.

00:37:20.570 --> 00:37:21.820
They didn't watch it together.

00:37:21.820 --> 00:37:24.640
They're just time-locked
to be shown together.

00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:29.500
And let's see, to orient
you, the more red and orange

00:37:29.500 --> 00:37:31.360
you can see on the
color bar over there,

00:37:31.360 --> 00:37:33.100
the more activity
that's occurring

00:37:33.100 --> 00:37:34.460
in that part of the brain.

00:37:34.460 --> 00:37:37.970
And the more green and
blue, the less activity.

00:37:37.970 --> 00:37:39.970
And so I think you'll be
able to hear the sound.

00:37:39.970 --> 00:37:40.750
We'll just watch this.

00:37:40.750 --> 00:37:42.340
It's a 20-second video,
but hopefully you

00:37:42.340 --> 00:37:44.560
can see the synchrony
occurring with your own eyes.

