00:38:43.270 --> 00:38:45.970
They are not responding
at all the same way

00:38:45.970 --> 00:38:47.750
to what they're taking in.

00:38:47.750 --> 00:38:49.690
And so this is really,
really cool-- at least,

00:38:49.690 --> 00:38:51.130
I think it's really
cool-- that we

00:38:51.130 --> 00:38:53.860
can tell this without
asking people,

00:38:53.860 --> 00:38:54.910
how distracted were you?

00:38:54.910 --> 00:38:57.700
Imagine at a
conference room meeting

00:38:57.700 --> 00:38:59.830
and you're going to ask
everyone, so how distracted

00:38:59.830 --> 00:39:00.996
were you during the meeting?

00:39:00.996 --> 00:39:02.950
Nobody's going to
say, I was distracted.

00:39:02.950 --> 00:39:05.116
They're all going to say,
oh, I was totally present.

00:39:05.116 --> 00:39:07.750
And man, I'm having great
ideas after that meeting.

00:39:07.750 --> 00:39:09.859
But we all know that
we've been that person,

00:39:09.859 --> 00:39:12.400
and there's other people who
are being that person right now.

00:39:12.400 --> 00:39:14.801
Some of you have no idea what
I'm talking about right now

00:39:14.801 --> 00:39:17.300
because you're being that person
right now, and that's fine.

00:39:17.300 --> 00:39:18.040
I have no problem with that.

00:39:18.040 --> 00:39:19.415
Because if I was
in the audience,

00:39:19.415 --> 00:39:20.954
I might be that person.

00:39:20.954 --> 00:39:22.870
But I think that's a
really interesting thing,

00:39:22.870 --> 00:39:27.960
to be able to detect that, I
think, in a pretty robust way.

00:39:27.960 --> 00:39:30.310
So let me tell you
about something

00:39:30.310 --> 00:39:32.320
that we've done
with this where we

00:39:32.320 --> 00:39:35.090
can show it's really about
people sharing perspective.

00:39:37.770 --> 00:39:39.890
So we take the equipment.

00:39:39.890 --> 00:39:42.750
We put it in our
carry-on luggage.

00:39:42.750 --> 00:39:46.010
This is Google Earth, so thank
you, Google, for making this.

00:39:46.010 --> 00:39:48.260
This impresses people at
every other talk I give,

00:39:48.260 --> 00:39:53.120
but I assume it would be
like, ugh, that again, here.

00:39:53.120 --> 00:39:56.790
So we go halfway around
the world to Amman, Jordan.

00:39:56.790 --> 00:39:58.550
And for the last
three summers, we've

00:39:58.550 --> 00:40:01.130
set up pop-up mobile
neuroscience labs,

00:40:01.130 --> 00:40:03.350
ran the first ever
social neuroscience

00:40:03.350 --> 00:40:08.000
studies run anywhere in
the country or the region.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:12.170
And what we were doing
in this particular study

00:40:12.170 --> 00:40:14.450
that I'm going to
tell you about is

00:40:14.450 --> 00:40:17.300
we found participants
over there who

00:40:17.300 --> 00:40:20.780
were either pro-choice
or pro-life with respect

00:40:20.780 --> 00:40:21.420
to abortion.

00:40:21.420 --> 00:40:23.600
Now, there is an important
debate over there

00:40:23.600 --> 00:40:24.830
that's pro-life, pro-choice.

00:40:24.830 --> 00:40:27.320
It's not the same as our debate.

00:40:27.320 --> 00:40:30.680
There's a general belief
that abortion is wrong.

00:40:30.680 --> 00:40:32.690
But there is a debate
over whether or not

00:40:32.690 --> 00:40:35.270
there should be an exception
in the case of rape.

00:40:35.270 --> 00:40:37.640
So that's what this
particular debate is about,

00:40:37.640 --> 00:40:39.530
and there's lots of
people on both sides.

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:42.770
It's about a 50/50 split, which
is what we were looking for.

00:40:42.770 --> 00:40:50.030
And then we had videos made
of local individuals arguing

00:40:50.030 --> 00:40:53.720
basically for the pro-choice
side or the pro-life side.

00:40:53.720 --> 00:40:57.080
So we have videos,
native-language videos,

00:40:57.080 --> 00:40:59.870
where people are arguing for
these two different sides.

00:40:59.870 --> 00:41:05.112
And both groups saw both
videos while wearing fNIRS.

00:41:05.112 --> 00:41:07.070
So then I'll take you
through what we looked at

00:41:07.070 --> 00:41:08.180
and how this works.

00:41:08.180 --> 00:41:12.180
So both groups watched
this pro-choice video.

00:41:12.180 --> 00:41:14.330
So let's say we pull
out one of the people

00:41:14.330 --> 00:41:16.130
from the pro-choice side.

00:41:16.130 --> 00:41:18.380
So conceptually,
they're down here now.

00:41:18.380 --> 00:41:20.640
Pretend they're not
up there anymore.

00:41:20.640 --> 00:41:22.280
And so what we can
do is we can look

00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:25.760
at the extent to which
this individual is showing

00:41:25.760 --> 00:41:29.030
a synchronous response
with the average of all

00:41:29.030 --> 00:41:31.787
the pro-choice folks up there.

00:41:31.787 --> 00:41:33.620
And you can do this
iteratively, so then you

00:41:33.620 --> 00:41:35.745
pull out a different subject
and put this one back.

00:41:35.745 --> 00:41:37.670
And you do it for
everyone so that you

00:41:37.670 --> 00:41:39.380
see how each person
is correlated

00:41:39.380 --> 00:41:41.850
with the rest of the group
in the pro-choice group.

00:41:41.850 --> 00:41:43.614
And when you do
this, what you see

00:41:43.614 --> 00:41:45.030
is that there's
lots of synchrony.

00:41:45.030 --> 00:41:48.680
So red on the scale
is up at the high end,

00:41:48.680 --> 00:41:51.480
and then yellow is also
pretty high as well.

00:41:51.480 --> 00:41:53.162
So we see lots of
synchrony there.

00:41:53.162 --> 00:41:54.620
But when we do the
same thing where

00:41:54.620 --> 00:41:58.010
we take someone who's pro-choice
and see how their brain

00:41:58.010 --> 00:42:00.350
responses correlate with
the folks who are pro-life,

00:42:00.350 --> 00:42:04.040
it's basically zero correlations
throughout the brain,

00:42:04.040 --> 00:42:06.890
throughout the frontal
cortex where we were looking.

00:42:06.890 --> 00:42:10.070
So they're seeing
the exact same video.

00:42:10.070 --> 00:42:12.170
The same photons are
hitting their eyes.

00:42:12.170 --> 00:42:14.120
The same sound waves
are hitting their ears.

00:42:14.120 --> 00:42:17.690
But they experience it like
them and not like them,

00:42:17.690 --> 00:42:20.300
and that's what's
coming out here.

00:42:20.300 --> 00:42:21.720
And we can reverse it.

00:42:21.720 --> 00:42:24.710
So now you pull someone out
from the pro-life group,

00:42:24.710 --> 00:42:27.060
and they'll show synchrony
with the pro-life group

00:42:27.060 --> 00:42:30.590
but not with the pro-choice
group-- just for complete sake.

00:42:30.590 --> 00:42:33.230
And so once we started
getting results like this,

00:42:33.230 --> 00:42:35.090
we started thinking
that there were

00:42:35.090 --> 00:42:37.460
a wide range of applications.

00:42:37.460 --> 00:42:41.960
And so one of the other people
in my department prodded me,

00:42:41.960 --> 00:42:43.700
and so we went and
started a company

00:42:43.700 --> 00:42:45.680
so that we could do
this in other places

00:42:45.680 --> 00:42:50.600
where we wouldn't ordinarily
study this inside UCLA.

00:42:50.600 --> 00:42:53.600
And so the idea
here is that as long

00:42:53.600 --> 00:42:56.540
as we have two different kinds
of reference groups getting

00:42:56.540 --> 00:42:59.600
at a particular kind
of way of experiencing

00:42:59.600 --> 00:43:03.680
a piece of the world, we
can now basically figure out

00:43:03.680 --> 00:43:06.962
what a new case is actually
seeing and experiencing

00:43:06.962 --> 00:43:09.170
when they're looking at
something because we can look

00:43:09.170 --> 00:43:11.711
at the extent to which they look
like more of a match for one

00:43:11.711 --> 00:43:13.410
group or another.

00:43:13.410 --> 00:43:16.760
And this lets us basically
and broadly speaking

00:43:16.760 --> 00:43:18.900
study the science
of compatibility.

00:43:18.900 --> 00:43:22.270
And it's in a very broad
kind of definition.

00:43:22.270 --> 00:43:24.470
And so the idea here is if
you experience something

00:43:24.470 --> 00:43:27.980
in similar ways as
another person or group,

00:43:27.980 --> 00:43:30.200
then you'll show greater
synchrony with that person

00:43:30.200 --> 00:43:32.990
or group under the proper
stimulus conditions.

00:43:32.990 --> 00:43:37.010
So the pro-choice person
watching a pro-choice video--

00:43:37.010 --> 00:43:40.670
not watching the Super Bowl, but
watching the pro-choice video--

00:43:40.670 --> 00:43:43.430
then they're experiencing
something in the same way

00:43:43.430 --> 00:43:45.690
or similar way to those folks.

00:43:45.690 --> 00:43:47.730
And so then you can
see that sort of thing.

00:43:47.730 --> 00:43:50.370
So imagine instead
of looking at this,

00:43:50.370 --> 00:43:52.640
we were trying to figure
out who in a company

00:43:52.640 --> 00:43:55.250
is experiencing
burnout right now.

00:43:55.250 --> 00:43:57.020
Some people in
this room right now

00:43:57.020 --> 00:43:59.147
are feeling burned out working.

00:43:59.147 --> 00:44:00.230
It's a fact of the matter.

00:44:00.230 --> 00:44:02.030
There's a decent
percentage of people

00:44:02.030 --> 00:44:05.120
that are feeling burned
out, and it's a big problem.

00:44:05.120 --> 00:44:06.860
People who are burned out leave.

00:44:06.860 --> 00:44:09.290
Before they leave, their
productivity goes way down.

00:44:09.290 --> 00:44:11.100
Burnout is contagious.

00:44:11.100 --> 00:44:13.700
It's something that anyone
running a company or somewhere

00:44:13.700 --> 00:44:16.094
up in management really,
really wants to avoid.

00:44:16.094 --> 00:44:17.510
But you can't go
to your employees

00:44:17.510 --> 00:44:20.300
and say, tell me, on a scale
from 1 to 10, how burned out

00:44:20.300 --> 00:44:21.590
are you feeling?

00:44:21.590 --> 00:44:23.725
Because people are typically
not going to tell you.

00:44:23.725 --> 00:44:25.100
That's not one of
those things we

00:44:25.100 --> 00:44:29.330
reveal in interviews and
performance reviews and things

00:44:29.330 --> 00:44:30.660
like that.

00:44:30.660 --> 00:44:32.300
But we could do the
same kind of thing

00:44:32.300 --> 00:44:35.466
we did with the
pro-choice, pro-life.

00:44:35.466 --> 00:44:37.740
But now, instead of looking
at pro-choice, pro-life,

00:44:37.740 --> 00:44:41.340
we're looking at videos
of CEOs and executives

00:44:41.340 --> 00:44:45.272
talking about feeling really
engaged or feeling burned out.

00:44:45.272 --> 00:44:46.980
And then we have people
that have already

00:44:46.980 --> 00:44:50.070
told us that they are feeling
engaged or burned out,

00:44:50.070 --> 00:44:53.430
and we can see how they respond
when they watch these videos

00:44:53.430 --> 00:44:56.894
and look at how that relates
to individuals in this way.

00:44:56.894 --> 00:44:59.310
So to get at this-- it's hard
to get a bunch of executives

00:44:59.310 --> 00:45:01.280
and CEOs in a room.

00:45:01.280 --> 00:45:03.280
They don't like to all
show up at the same time,

00:45:03.280 --> 00:45:05.040
so we went to them.

00:45:05.040 --> 00:45:07.980
A few months ago, we went
to this event, Summit LA.

00:45:07.980 --> 00:45:12.120
It's an ideas fest for
basically really wealthy CEOs

00:45:12.120 --> 00:45:13.260
and executives.

00:45:13.260 --> 00:45:15.360
I could never afford
to go to this event

00:45:15.360 --> 00:45:18.420
unless I was invited,
which I was, thankfully.

00:45:18.420 --> 00:45:22.240
And so once we were there,
people say yes to everything.

00:45:22.240 --> 00:45:24.240
And so we were super
excited that a bunch

00:45:24.240 --> 00:45:27.000
of CEOs and executives were
happy to come in and get

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:28.740
their brains scanned together.

00:45:28.740 --> 00:45:31.620
This is literally the first
time four people have ever

00:45:31.620 --> 00:45:33.750
been scanned while
having a conversation.

00:45:33.750 --> 00:45:36.220
That's never
happened in any form.

00:45:36.220 --> 00:45:38.400
So we thought that was
pretty cool in and of itself.

00:45:38.400 --> 00:45:40.380
And they did interesting
things while they

00:45:40.380 --> 00:45:41.820
were having conversations.

00:45:41.820 --> 00:45:44.100
I'm not going to tell you
about that data today.

00:45:44.100 --> 00:45:46.360
But another thing they
did is at one point--

00:45:46.360 --> 00:45:47.550
there's a TV here--

00:45:47.550 --> 00:45:50.190
they all turned and
looked at the TV,

00:45:50.190 --> 00:45:52.350
and they watched
videos like these.

00:45:52.350 --> 00:45:54.540
So they saw some people
talking about how

00:45:54.540 --> 00:45:56.964
engaged and excited they
are at work, like this guy.

00:45:56.964 --> 00:45:57.630
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:45:57.630 --> 00:45:59.520
- What's really exciting
to me personally

00:45:59.520 --> 00:46:03.270
is the ability to make an impact
for millions if not billions

00:46:03.270 --> 00:46:07.320
of people, having a commercially
successful product that

00:46:07.320 --> 00:46:09.780
is driven by technology
but ultimately making

00:46:09.780 --> 00:46:10.990
the human experience better.

00:46:10.990 --> 00:46:13.180
We get a lot of messages
saying, thank you,

00:46:13.180 --> 00:46:15.750
Ivy-- which is our hotel
concierge that we created.

00:46:15.750 --> 00:46:17.310
By texting you, I
was able to get it

00:46:17.310 --> 00:46:20.040
in two minutes at my door
and that really, you're

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:21.180
a lifesaver.

