about being a CEO.

00:46:41.250 --> 00:46:42.030
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:46:42.030 --> 00:46:43.810
- You know, it's a very
stressful environment.

00:46:43.810 --> 00:46:45.310
It's sort of
high-risk, high-reward.

00:46:45.310 --> 00:46:47.412
You've got a lot riding
on pulling it off,

00:46:47.412 --> 00:46:49.245
and that falls on the
CEO and on management.

00:46:49.245 --> 00:46:51.900
And you've got your
investors relying on you.

00:46:51.900 --> 00:46:53.410
You've got your employees who--

00:46:55.632 --> 00:46:57.840
that's their job, and they're
feeding their families,

00:46:57.840 --> 00:46:58.900
and they're living.

00:46:58.900 --> 00:47:02.697
And so a lot of times, it
gets very close to the flame.

00:47:02.697 --> 00:47:03.280
[END PLAYBACK]

00:47:03.280 --> 00:47:05.446
MATTHEW LIEBERMAN: OK, so
imagine that you're either

00:47:05.446 --> 00:47:06.960
feeling super jazzed
about the work

00:47:06.960 --> 00:47:08.490
you're doing-- you're
right where you should be--

00:47:08.490 --> 00:47:09.796
or you're feeling burned out.

00:47:09.796 --> 00:47:11.670
You're probably going
to experience these two

00:47:11.670 --> 00:47:14.550
kinds of videos
differently based

00:47:14.550 --> 00:47:17.264
on what's going on with
you in your life right now.

00:47:17.264 --> 00:47:18.930
And so that's what
we wanted to look at.

00:47:18.930 --> 00:47:21.630
So basically, everything
I'm going to show you

00:47:21.630 --> 00:47:23.700
is from this same
medial prefrontal spot

00:47:23.700 --> 00:47:26.500
that I've shown you in some of
the previous studies before.

00:47:26.500 --> 00:47:29.130
It seems to be
associated with identity

00:47:29.130 --> 00:47:32.670
and integrating things and
identifying with something

00:47:32.670 --> 00:47:34.180
that you're taking in.

00:47:34.180 --> 00:47:38.430
And so what we see is that when
people are watching the what

00:47:38.430 --> 00:47:42.000
do you love about what you do
types of videos, what we see

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:45.630
is that the engaged
CEOs and executives--

00:47:45.630 --> 00:47:48.600
they show a fair amount of
synchrony with one another

00:47:48.600 --> 00:47:50.260
in that condition.

00:47:50.260 --> 00:47:52.050
But the folks who are
feeling burned out

00:47:52.050 --> 00:47:53.700
don't really show
any synchrony when

00:47:53.700 --> 00:47:56.430
they're watching these
folks talk about how excited

00:47:56.430 --> 00:47:57.747
and engaged they are.

00:47:57.747 --> 00:48:00.330
When you see the folks talking
about being stressed and burned

00:48:00.330 --> 00:48:02.850
out, now instead,
you see the burned

00:48:02.850 --> 00:48:06.600
out folks who are sort
of stressed and feeling

00:48:06.600 --> 00:48:09.960
the pressure-- these folks are
showing more synchrony with one

00:48:09.960 --> 00:48:13.920
another than the
executives who are engaged

00:48:13.920 --> 00:48:15.040
and thriving and so on.

00:48:15.040 --> 00:48:17.550
So putting that together,
what you essentially

00:48:17.550 --> 00:48:21.570
see is that the engaged
CEOs show a lot more

00:48:21.570 --> 00:48:24.960
synchrony for the engaged
videos, and the folks who

00:48:24.960 --> 00:48:28.770
are feeling more burned out show
more synchrony with the burnout

00:48:28.770 --> 00:48:30.870
videos, the stress videos.

00:48:30.870 --> 00:48:33.690
And we were actually,
using very simple machine

00:48:33.690 --> 00:48:38.010
learning classification,
able to classify about 85%

00:48:38.010 --> 00:48:42.900
of the folks who were feeling
burned out as being burned out

00:48:42.900 --> 00:48:45.010
based on their brain data.

00:48:45.010 --> 00:48:47.760
And so I think that's
a promising thing

00:48:47.760 --> 00:48:51.120
because doing this, you don't
actually have to go ask folks.

00:48:51.120 --> 00:48:53.520
We knew because we were
running that kind of study.

00:48:53.520 --> 00:48:55.020
But in the future,
it could be used

00:48:55.020 --> 00:48:58.590
in an application where you
don't know in advance who's

00:48:58.590 --> 00:49:00.240
feeling one way or the other.

00:49:00.240 --> 00:49:03.150
I'll just mention a couple of
the other applications of this

00:49:03.150 --> 00:49:05.510
before I stop.

00:49:05.510 --> 00:49:06.830
Dana Landis isn't here, right?

00:49:06.830 --> 00:49:07.460
Is that right?

00:49:07.460 --> 00:49:08.250
No, OK.

00:49:08.250 --> 00:49:11.370
So Dana Landis is at
Google, but she's also

00:49:11.370 --> 00:49:13.020
on our advisory board.

00:49:13.020 --> 00:49:17.580
And so we've talked with her
about working towards solutions

00:49:17.580 --> 00:49:18.840
for the diversity pipeline.

00:49:18.840 --> 00:49:20.190
I know you guys have it in tech.

00:49:20.190 --> 00:49:21.840
We have it in academia.

00:49:21.840 --> 00:49:24.030
It's a genuine,
real issue that's

00:49:24.030 --> 00:49:25.890
really, really hard to solve.

00:49:25.890 --> 00:49:27.780
And one of the things
that we've talked

00:49:27.780 --> 00:49:32.310
about is that you can go to
folks who aren't necessarily

00:49:32.310 --> 00:49:34.836
getting exposed to
the best training

00:49:34.836 --> 00:49:36.960
and they're not getting it
in an environment-- say,

00:49:36.960 --> 00:49:41.950
in an inner-city school
environment, elementary school,

00:49:41.950 --> 00:49:44.820
middle school, and so on, where
not only are you not getting

00:49:44.820 --> 00:49:47.220
it, but there's not a lot
of emphasis in the family

00:49:47.220 --> 00:49:49.380
or among friends
to really cultivate

00:49:49.380 --> 00:49:52.200
an attitude towards what
I should spend my time

00:49:52.200 --> 00:49:55.121
and energy on is learning how
to do algebra or something

00:49:55.121 --> 00:49:55.620
like that.

00:49:55.620 --> 00:49:57.300
It's just not
necessarily especially

00:49:57.300 --> 00:50:00.790
valued, for understandable
reasons, in that context.

00:50:00.790 --> 00:50:02.940
But if you can go
in and actually look

00:50:02.940 --> 00:50:05.190
at who shows brain
responses when

00:50:05.190 --> 00:50:07.740
they look at certain
mathematical or other types

00:50:07.740 --> 00:50:11.160
of STEM concepts that even
look a bit more like folks who

00:50:11.160 --> 00:50:13.230
have excelled in that
region, could you

00:50:13.230 --> 00:50:16.500
identify aptitude in folks
who aren't going to show it

00:50:16.500 --> 00:50:17.580
on traditional tests.

00:50:17.580 --> 00:50:19.800
And there's some reasons
to think that you actually

00:50:19.800 --> 00:50:20.300
can do this.

00:50:20.300 --> 00:50:22.466
And so this is something
where if you could identify

00:50:22.466 --> 00:50:24.000
those folks when
they're young, you

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.790
could bring them over
summers to summer institutes

00:50:26.790 --> 00:50:31.380
where they get some of the kinds
of exposure and norm setting

00:50:31.380 --> 00:50:34.470
that would lead people to
get to a place like Google

00:50:34.470 --> 00:50:36.630
where they probably
wouldn't otherwise.

00:50:36.630 --> 00:50:39.300
And probably the idea that
I'm most excited about

00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:41.520
is that if we can get data
from the other work we're

00:50:41.520 --> 00:50:45.390
doing on what thriving,
engaged brains look

00:50:45.390 --> 00:50:48.192
like in a bunch of
different careers,

00:50:48.192 --> 00:50:49.650
then you could
develop what we call

00:50:49.650 --> 00:50:51.540
the neural guidance counselor,
where you could take

00:50:51.540 --> 00:50:53.910
a 17-year-old who has no idea
what to do with their life--

00:50:53.910 --> 00:50:55.620
and if you go to a regular
guidance counselor,

00:50:55.620 --> 00:50:57.578
you're not going to get
any better idea of what

00:50:57.578 --> 00:50:58.542
to do with your life.

00:50:58.542 --> 00:51:00.750
I don't know that anyone's
ever had a good experience

00:51:00.750 --> 00:51:02.010
with a guidance counselor.

00:51:02.010 --> 00:51:04.680
They're either
neutral or creepy.

00:51:04.680 --> 00:51:06.790
Like, those are the two options.

00:51:06.790 --> 00:51:09.150
But what if you could
basically go find out,

00:51:09.150 --> 00:51:12.690
OK, well, these are the things
where you, as a 17-year-old,

00:51:12.690 --> 00:51:15.720
you look at certain things in
a way that's at least a bit

00:51:15.720 --> 00:51:18.180
similar to people in
certain professions

00:51:18.180 --> 00:51:21.990
who are both productive,
successful, and really happy

00:51:21.990 --> 00:51:25.194
doing that job?

00:51:25.194 --> 00:51:27.360
There's lots of other things
to think about in terms

00:51:27.360 --> 00:51:29.380
of team construction.

00:51:29.380 --> 00:51:30.810
So we had these
groups at Summit,

00:51:30.810 --> 00:51:33.332
and they were having
conversations with each other.

00:51:33.332 --> 00:51:35.040
And there's lots of
interesting dynamics,

00:51:35.040 --> 00:51:38.160
like we varied the gender
composition of the groups

00:51:38.160 --> 00:51:39.312
across the sessions.

00:51:39.312 --> 00:51:41.020
And we don't have that
data analyzed yet,

00:51:41.020 --> 00:51:43.020
but we're really,
really interested to see

00:51:43.020 --> 00:51:44.940
how synchrony
profiles change when

00:51:44.940 --> 00:51:48.187
it's zero women, one woman,
two women, three women, so on.

00:51:48.187 --> 00:51:49.770
That's going to be
really interesting.

00:51:49.770 --> 00:51:53.550
Also, some of these people are
the same people who told us

00:51:53.550 --> 00:51:55.200
they were feeling burned out.

00:51:55.200 --> 00:51:58.020
It turns out the people who
are feeling burned out also

00:51:58.020 --> 00:52:00.900
reported being the least
interested and engaged

00:52:00.900 --> 00:52:02.610
in what anyone else
had to say when

00:52:02.610 --> 00:52:04.110
they were at these sessions.

00:52:04.110 --> 00:52:07.620
So here's a way in which the
burnout feature is actually

00:52:07.620 --> 00:52:10.864
having a genuine impact on the
way they interact with others.

00:52:10.864 --> 00:52:12.780
And when the folks who
were feeling burned out

00:52:12.780 --> 00:52:16.770
was asked who was the most
interesting, engaging person

00:52:16.770 --> 00:52:19.830
at the table, they were
much more likely than anyone

00:52:19.830 --> 00:52:22.030
else to say, me.

00:52:22.030 --> 00:52:24.510
Most other people pointed to
someone else at the table--

00:52:24.510 --> 00:52:25.530
I mean, in writing--

00:52:25.530 --> 00:52:27.600
and said, oh, that person
was really interesting.

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:29.600
But the folks who were
feeling burned out-- they

00:52:29.600 --> 00:52:31.740
said, I guess I was the
only interesting person

00:52:31.740 --> 00:52:33.210
at the table.

00:52:33.210 --> 00:52:37.692
Last thing is that there's
the obvious application

00:52:37.692 --> 00:52:39.150
that this actually
directly applies

00:52:39.150 --> 00:52:42.450
to regular old matchmaking.

00:52:42.450 --> 00:52:44.880
And we've thought
about this a fair bit,

00:52:44.880 --> 00:52:47.730
but we think that this gets
at a kind of compatibility

00:52:47.730 --> 00:52:51.990
where when you use
Tinder or whatever else,

00:52:51.990 --> 00:52:55.860
there's no measurement of
compatibility on match.com

00:52:55.860 --> 00:52:58.260
or eharmony, who
even used to pretend

00:52:58.260 --> 00:52:59.430
that they did compatibility.

00:52:59.430 --> 00:53:00.907
It turns out it wasn't.

00:53:00.907 --> 00:53:02.490
There's interesting
stories about that

00:53:02.490 --> 00:53:04.140
that I won't go into.

00:53:04.140 --> 00:53:07.020
But you can actually
measure compatibility

00:53:07.020 --> 00:53:09.000
in a meaningful sort of way.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:10.950
You want to find people--

00:53:10.950 --> 00:53:13.610
the person that you want to
find and spend your life with

00:53:13.610 --> 00:53:15.750
is probably going
to be someone that

00:53:15.750 --> 00:53:19.350
actually in meaningful ways
sees the world similarly

00:53:19.350 --> 00:53:22.710
to the way you see it-- not
visually, but conceptually.

00:53:22.710 --> 00:53:24.640
And this is a way
to get at that.

00:53:24.640 --> 00:53:27.750
And there is data that suggests
that this, in fact, can predict

00:53:27.750 --> 00:53:29.880
who will become friends.

00:53:29.880 --> 00:53:32.190
And there's no reason to
think it couldn't predict

00:53:32.190 --> 00:53:35.284
who would become friends
that are more than friends

00:53:35.284 --> 00:53:37.200
if you take into account
attraction and things

00:53:37.200 --> 00:53:38.830
like that.

00:53:38.830 --> 00:53:41.940
So I think that's a really
interesting feature of this

00:53:41.940 --> 00:53:42.720
as well.

00:53:42.720 --> 00:53:48.300
So I know that at this
point, I have gone long.

00:53:48.300 --> 00:53:51.413
And so I will stop
there and say thank you.

00:53:51.413 --> 00:53:53.621
And I'm happy to take any
questions if there are any.

00:53:53.621 --> 00:53:54.120
Thanks.

00:53:54.120 --> 00:53:58.200
[APPLAUSE]

00:53:58.200 --> 00:53:58.700
Yeah?

00:53:58.700 --> 00:54:01.690
AUDIENCE: So is there any sense
of what types of companies

00:54:01.690 --> 00:54:03.080
increase social interactions?

00:54:03.080 --> 00:54:04.790
What are the variables
that are relevant?

00:54:04.790 --> 00:54:06.230
One of the ones that
we talk about often

00:54:06.230 --> 00:54:07.790
is the open workspace
environment.

00:54:07.790 --> 00:54:10.250
There's a big study that
came out about it recently.

00:54:10.250 --> 00:54:11.990
Are there other
things like that that

00:54:11.990 --> 00:54:14.790
are useful when it comes to
increasing social interaction

00:54:14.790 --> 00:54:15.440
in a good way?

00:54:15.440 --> 00:54:17.706
MATTHEW LIEBERMAN: Yeah, sure.

00:54:17.706 --> 00:54:19.400
And I've given
talks for companies

00:54:19.400 --> 00:54:23.300
about creating agile workspaces
where nobody has their own desk

00:54:23.300 --> 00:54:24.770
or anything like that.

00:54:24.770 --> 00:54:28.152
It kind of seems like a disaster
to do that for lots of reasons.

00:54:28.152 --> 00:54:30.110
I think anyone who works
in one of those spaces

00:54:30.110 --> 00:54:33.440
knows you get a roomful of
people wearing headphones.

00:54:33.440 --> 00:54:35.360
But people also
feel a bit better

00:54:35.360 --> 00:54:36.800
if they have some
space ownership.

00:54:36.800 --> 00:54:38.900
It turns out a lot
of the motivation

00:54:38.900 --> 00:54:41.540
for making those kinds of
spaces is that the company can

00:54:41.540 --> 00:54:42.890
lease a lot less space.

00:54:42.890 --> 00:54:44.723
Because when you're not
there, somebody else

00:54:44.723 --> 00:54:46.490
can sit at the same desk, right?

00:54:46.490 --> 00:54:49.310
Now, there is
evidence that suggests

00:54:49.310 --> 00:54:53.420
that putting people in
proximity to each other

00:54:53.420 --> 00:54:54.450
is really important.

00:54:54.450 --> 00:54:57.320
So Humanyze-- who did the
thing with the water cooler,

00:54:57.320 --> 00:54:58.602
15-minute breaks, and so on--

00:54:58.602 --> 00:55:00.810
one of the other studies
they did is they looked at--

00:55:00.810 --> 00:55:03.654
I think this was with
Deutsche Bank or some bank.

00:55:03.654 --> 00:55:04.820
It may not be Deutsche Bank.

00:55:04.820 --> 00:55:07.430
I may just have that
on the brain lately.

00:55:07.430 --> 00:55:11.540
But they had different banks
where in some of the banks,

00:55:11.540 --> 00:55:16.130
everyone who worked in a certain
division was on the same floor.

00:55:16.130 --> 00:55:18.500
And in some companies,
they were just

00:55:18.500 --> 00:55:20.720
on slightly different
floors, like one floor

00:55:20.720 --> 00:55:24.410
apart with a stairwell
internal to it connecting them.

00:55:24.410 --> 00:55:25.910
And there were
dramatic differences.

00:55:25.910 --> 00:55:29.870
They managed to convince
them to switch one of these

00:55:29.870 --> 00:55:32.940
to one of these, and the
productivity went way up.

00:55:32.940 --> 00:55:34.580
And that seems to
be due to the fact

00:55:34.580 --> 00:55:38.480
that now you've created a better
case for social permeability

00:55:38.480 --> 00:55:41.130
so that people can connect
more easily and so on.

00:55:41.130 --> 00:55:45.800
I think the other thing is that
we tend to just not think about

00:55:45.800 --> 00:55:46.910
it very much.

00:55:46.910 --> 00:55:48.170
And so it's easy to do.

00:55:48.170 --> 00:55:48.800
I run a lab.

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:53.780
It's easy for me to forget that,
in some sense, part of my job

00:55:53.780 --> 00:55:57.290
is providing for and creating
the right social atmosphere.

00:55:57.290 --> 00:56:00.500
We think, well, I provide
my students with resources.

00:56:00.500 --> 00:56:04.170
And I try to give them good
advice and wisdom and so on.

00:56:04.170 --> 00:56:05.810
But this is also
where they're living

00:56:05.810 --> 00:56:08.120
part of their social
life for several years.

00:56:08.120 --> 00:56:10.450
We spend so many hours at work.

00:56:10.450 --> 00:56:13.070
That has to have some
of the same features

00:56:13.070 --> 00:56:15.080
that we look for
outside of work.

00:56:15.080 --> 00:56:16.514
And I think that
companies sort of

00:56:16.514 --> 00:56:17.930
think, well, I
don't want to spend

00:56:17.930 --> 00:56:19.680
extra money on those things.

00:56:19.680 --> 00:56:22.490
But it turns out you're not
because it reduces burnout.

00:56:22.490 --> 00:56:25.100
It reduces-- so it's a
good play for the company,

00:56:25.100 --> 00:56:29.190
but it's also really good for
the people who work there.

00:56:29.190 --> 00:56:32.570
AUDIENCE: fNIRS--
yeah, so I'm just

00:56:32.570 --> 00:56:35.660
thinking whether it could be
useful for personal, emotional

00:56:35.660 --> 00:56:37.200
development.

00:56:37.200 --> 00:56:40.570
How much does it cost, and
have you thought about that?

00:56:40.570 --> 00:56:41.570
MATTHEW LIEBERMAN: Sure.

00:56:44.147 --> 00:56:45.980
OK, so there is a couple
of answers to this.

00:56:45.980 --> 00:56:49.670
One is there's a lot of
fly-by-night equipment

00:56:49.670 --> 00:56:53.150
out on the market right now,
and the vast majority of it

00:56:53.150 --> 00:56:54.710
is junk.

00:56:54.710 --> 00:56:57.890
So there's a bunch of
portable EEG things

00:56:57.890 --> 00:57:00.740
where you get a single lead
that doesn't actually connect

00:57:00.740 --> 00:57:02.750
the right way to the scalp.

00:57:02.750 --> 00:57:05.180
You're supposed to use
certain kinds of leads

00:57:05.180 --> 00:57:07.875
that those don't because
they're messy and expensive.

00:57:07.875 --> 00:57:09.500
And so there's a lot
of stuff out there

00:57:09.500 --> 00:57:11.900
that's junk that
people are using that--

00:57:11.900 --> 00:57:13.700
I'm sure there's some
signal, but it's also

00:57:13.700 --> 00:57:16.260
a signal swamped by noise.

00:57:16.260 --> 00:57:19.820
fNIRS, like anything, has
some signal, some noise.

00:57:19.820 --> 00:57:22.070
But I've been convinced
that the signal

00:57:22.070 --> 00:57:25.430
is meaningful at this
point, although we're still

00:57:25.430 --> 00:57:27.170
testing those things.

00:57:27.170 --> 00:57:30.690
In terms of using
them for personal use,

00:57:30.690 --> 00:57:35.570
I do think that that is a
plausible longer time horizon

00:57:35.570 --> 00:57:36.110
scenario.

00:57:36.110 --> 00:57:39.472
Right now they are a
bit clunky to set up.

00:57:39.472 --> 00:57:41.180
You need a technician
there to set it up.

00:57:41.180 --> 00:57:42.805
I don't know that
you could effectively

00:57:42.805 --> 00:57:45.170
set up your own right now.

00:57:45.170 --> 00:57:48.470
But we are working with hardware
companies about engineering

00:57:48.470 --> 00:57:50.810
plans for how to make this
more consumer-friendly

00:57:50.810 --> 00:57:52.312
at some point down the road.

00:57:52.312 --> 00:57:54.770
So I think maybe in five years
we might be looking at that.

00:57:54.770 --> 00:57:59.180
If you wanted to buy
one for yourself,

00:57:59.180 --> 00:58:01.550
the lowest-end one
that I would think

00:58:01.550 --> 00:58:06.390
is really worth using is
probably about $100,000.

00:58:06.390 --> 00:58:08.630
There's toy ones that
you can get for $50,000,

00:58:08.630 --> 00:58:11.840
but I really do think they
are toys and very, very

00:58:11.840 --> 00:58:13.460
limited in what they can do.

00:58:13.460 --> 00:58:16.880
$100,000 would basically
get you with pretty good

00:58:16.880 --> 00:58:18.650
signal your prefrontal
cortex, and then it

00:58:18.650 --> 00:58:21.090
doubles and triples
and so on from there.

00:58:21.090 --> 00:58:23.780
And then in terms of the
other part of the question,

00:58:23.780 --> 00:58:27.230
could you use it for personal
emotional development,

00:58:27.230 --> 00:58:29.600
it would take something
really rigorous, I think,

00:58:29.600 --> 00:58:33.390
set up by some kind of
company to make that work.

00:58:33.390 --> 00:58:36.410
I don't think you could just sit
there and stare at your signal

00:58:36.410 --> 00:58:38.960
and say, OK, I'm going to
work these parts in my brain,

00:58:38.960 --> 00:58:40.985
and have that be
terribly meaningful.

00:58:40.985 --> 00:58:41.860
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:41.860 --> 00:58:44.690
MATTHEW LIEBERMAN: Yeah,
so we actually right now

00:58:44.690 --> 00:58:47.210
are starting our collaboration
with a clinical psychologist

00:58:47.210 --> 00:58:49.580
at UCLA, Michelle
Craske, where we're

00:58:49.580 --> 00:58:54.050
going to have both the therapist
and the client wear fNIRS

00:58:54.050 --> 00:58:54.860
during--

00:58:54.860 --> 00:58:58.200
they do, like, 12 sessions,
12 weeks of sessions.

00:58:58.200 --> 00:59:00.050
And so they're going
to do it in week 1,

00:59:00.050 --> 00:59:03.440
I think, week 3, 6, 9, and 12.

00:59:03.440 --> 00:59:05.450
And so we're very
interested in how

00:59:05.450 --> 00:59:07.910
the dynamics both
within the individuals

00:59:07.910 --> 00:59:10.760
and across the individuals
change over time

00:59:10.760 --> 00:59:13.730
and how that predicts
who feels like they've

00:59:13.730 --> 00:59:15.980
gotten the most out of it
and also who sticks with it.

00:59:15.980 --> 00:59:17.521
Because most people
actually drop out

00:59:17.521 --> 00:59:19.250
before they get to
what therapists say

00:59:19.250 --> 00:59:22.410
should be the natural
stopping point.

00:59:22.410 --> 00:59:25.890
AUDIENCE: I also have
a question about fNIRS.

00:59:25.890 --> 00:59:27.750
So the first thing
that popped in my head

00:59:27.750 --> 00:59:30.208
when you mentioned that it
could be used to measure burnout

00:59:30.208 --> 00:59:32.150
when people don't actually
actively report it

00:59:32.150 --> 00:59:34.800
is something like
"Black Mirror."

00:59:34.800 --> 00:59:37.060
Not to bias you,
but I was wondering,

00:59:37.060 --> 00:59:38.880
what do you see as
practically a way

00:59:38.880 --> 00:59:43.292
to get people to get
their burnout measured

00:59:43.292 --> 00:59:44.500
or something similar to that?

00:59:44.500 --> 00:59:45.600
And what are the
ethical implications

00:59:45.600 --> 00:59:46.710
of being able to do that?

00:59:46.710 --> 00:59:49.080
MATTHEW LIEBERMAN: Right,
so that's a good question.

00:59:49.080 --> 00:59:53.562
We get the burnout, the "Black
Mirror" comment very regularly.

00:59:53.562 --> 00:59:55.020
We actually, at
some point, thought

00:59:55.020 --> 00:59:57.105
about naming the
company something that

00:59:57.105 --> 00:59:58.980
would be an inside joke
about "Black Mirror",

00:59:58.980 --> 01:00:00.870
like something from one
of the episodes just

01:00:00.870 --> 01:00:05.280
to be really like, yep,
that's where we live.

01:00:05.280 --> 01:00:09.480
And I think that
really depends on how

01:00:09.480 --> 01:00:12.030
a company wants to
pitch what they're

01:00:12.030 --> 01:00:14.610
doing to their employees.

01:00:14.610 --> 01:00:17.790
So if finding out
folks are burned out

01:00:17.790 --> 01:00:20.500
is then used in some
threatening way,

01:00:20.500 --> 01:00:22.530
then that's not really
good for anyone.

01:00:22.530 --> 01:00:25.770
But if it's used in a way
to direct more resources

01:00:25.770 --> 01:00:29.520
and to help folks who are
vulnerable for leaving

01:00:29.520 --> 01:00:32.070
the company or who might
benefit from certain types

01:00:32.070 --> 01:00:34.860
of interventions, then
that's something that I think

01:00:34.860 --> 01:00:36.210
is probably more positive.

01:00:36.210 --> 01:00:38.029
But I totally agree
that there's some uses

01:00:38.029 --> 01:00:40.320
of what we're doing, like
the neural guidance counselor

01:00:40.320 --> 01:00:41.251
thing--

01:00:41.251 --> 01:00:43.500
that's a pure benefit for
anyone who goes and does it.

01:00:43.500 --> 01:00:46.320
If you're 17 and you go
and do this, you get told,

01:00:46.320 --> 01:00:49.470
you're a 90% match with this
and a 30% match with that

01:00:49.470 --> 01:00:50.900
and do with that what you want.

01:00:50.900 --> 01:00:52.650
But you might not have
known these things.

01:00:52.650 --> 01:00:54.360
A lot of us grow
up thinking, well,

01:00:54.360 --> 01:00:56.920
I should do what my parents
did, or something like that.

01:00:56.920 --> 01:00:59.370
Or we get into a random
internship after college

01:00:59.370 --> 01:01:02.440
and suddenly, that's our
career 20 years later.

01:01:02.440 --> 01:01:04.620
This is a way to sort
of try out things

01:01:04.620 --> 01:01:07.240
that you could never
go try out on your own.

01:01:07.240 --> 01:01:10.290
So I think that there's a range
of different applications.

01:01:10.290 --> 01:01:14.250
And some of them, I think that
folks who want to use this

01:01:14.250 --> 01:01:16.560
will have to think about,
well, what are the benefits

01:01:16.560 --> 01:01:17.490
that a person gets?

01:01:17.490 --> 01:01:19.290
And there are lots of
potential benefits.

01:01:19.290 --> 01:01:21.555
So you could get
information yourself

01:01:21.555 --> 01:01:23.430
that relates not
necessarily just to burnout.

01:01:23.430 --> 01:01:25.530
If you're feeling burned
out, you probably know that.

01:01:25.530 --> 01:01:26.904
But there's a lot
of other things

01:01:26.904 --> 01:01:29.670
about the extent to which you
show certain kinds of skills

01:01:29.670 --> 01:01:31.530
and aptitudes and so on.

01:01:31.530 --> 01:01:33.780
People love things
like the Myers-Briggs,

01:01:33.780 --> 01:01:35.380
even though it's complete junk.

01:01:35.380 --> 01:01:37.650
It doesn't actually tell
you anything meaningfully.

01:01:37.650 --> 01:01:42.554
Any psychometrician will say,
don't ever, ever use that.

01:01:42.554 --> 01:01:44.220
But people are really,
really interested

01:01:44.220 --> 01:01:47.389
because they want to get this
kind of standardized feedback.

01:01:47.389 --> 01:01:48.930
And I think that is
one of the things

01:01:48.930 --> 01:01:50.520
that this could be used to do.

01:01:50.520 --> 01:01:52.270
We haven't done
that specifically,

01:01:52.270 --> 01:01:54.930
but I think it could be used
in some of those domains.

01:01:54.930 --> 01:01:57.450
And it could be
used to see if you

01:01:57.450 --> 01:01:59.891
qualify to get certain kinds
of trainings or promotions

01:01:59.891 --> 01:02:00.390
or whatever.

01:02:00.390 --> 01:02:02.207
So you could have
your brain scan-- so

01:02:02.207 --> 01:02:03.790
imagine the neural
guidance counselor,

01:02:03.790 --> 01:02:06.210
and it says, you're a
great match for this.

01:02:06.210 --> 01:02:08.460
But you don't test well
and things like that.

01:02:08.460 --> 01:02:11.460
This could become, in
part, a partial substitute,

01:02:11.460 --> 01:02:13.440
where you say, well,
I don't test well,

01:02:13.440 --> 01:02:15.510
but I'll probably do
the actual thing well.

01:02:15.510 --> 01:02:17.130
Because my brain
looks like the people

01:02:17.130 --> 01:02:18.900
who do the actual thing well.

01:02:18.900 --> 01:02:20.710
That's an interesting
possibility.

